{"title_page": "Avintia Racing", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox Grand Prix motorcycle team\n|Short_name=Avintia Racing\n|Logo=[[Image:Reale_Avintia_Racing_Logo_2018.jpg|120px]]\n|Last_season=2019|\n|Long_name=Reale Avintia Racing|\n|Base= [[Madrid]], Spain\n|Principal=Ra\u00fal Romero\n|Riders={{nowrap|'''MotoGP''':<br>5.  [[Johann Zarco]] \n<br>53.  [[Tito Rabat]] <br>'''Moto3''':<br> 99. [[Carlos Tatay]]}}<br> '''MotoE''':<br>20. [[Xavier Cardelus]]<br>51. [[Eric Granado]]\n|Motorcycle={{nowrap|MotoE \u2013 [[Energica Motor Company|Energica]]<br>MotoGP \u2013 [[Ducati]]<br>Moto3 \u2013 [[KTM]]}}\n|Tyres={{nowrap|MotoE \u2013 [[Michelin]]<br>MotoGP \u2013 [[Michelin]]}}<br>{{nowrap|Moto3 \u2013 [[Dunlop Tyres|Dunlop]]}}\n|Riders_champ=\n}}\n\n'''Avintia Racing''' is a [[motorcycle racing]] team currently competing in the [[MotoGP]] and [[Moto3]] World Championships under the name '''Reale Avintia Racing''' and a [[Spain|Spanish]] license, as well as in the [[MotoE World Cup]] under the name '''Avintia Esponsorama Racing''' and an [[Andorra|Andorran]] license.\n\n==History==\n===Domestic racing===\nThe team was set up in 1994 by Raul Romero and Josep Oliva as '''By Queroseno Racing''', also known as '''Team BQR'''. Competing in the Spanish Road Racing Championship (Campeonato de Espa\u00f1a de Velocidad), BQR won three ''F\u00f3rmula Extreme'' and two ''125GP'' class titles with riders [[Jos\u00e9 David de Gea]], [[Stefan Bradl]] and [[Efr\u00e9n V\u00e1zquez]].\n\n===Grand Prix racing===\n====125cc and 250cc classes====\nAfter many wild card appearances in the World Championship, BQR became a full entry in the [[2001 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2001 season]] using [[Honda]] bikes in the 250cc class. In [[2007 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2007]] the team switched to [[Aprilia]] machinery. BQR won its first World Championship race with [[Scott Redding]] riding an Aprilia 125 at the [[2008 British motorcycle Grand_Prix|2008 British Grand Prix]].\n\n==== Moto3 ====\nIn [[2017 Moto3 season|2017]], Avintia entered [[Vicente P\u00e9rez (motorcyclist)|Vicente P\u00e9rez]] in 2 races as a wildcard. For [[2018 Moto3 season|2018]] the team entered a single full-season entry, beginning the season with [[Livio Loi]] for the first seven rounds and replacing him with P\u00e9rez for the remainder of the season. In [[2019 Moto3 season|2019]] the team began with P\u00e9rez for the first seven rounds, but replacing him with [[Stefano Nepa]] for the remaining races, and addition to a number of wildcard entries for Nepa, [[Meikon Kawakami]], and [[Carlos Tatay]]. In [[2020 Moto3 season|2020]], Avintia entered Tatay as their sole full-season entry.\n\n====Moto2====\nThe team unveiled the first [[Moto2]] bike in February 2009 and fielded a prototype in the 2009 Spanish Road Racing Championship.  In [[2010 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2010]], they participated in the new Moto2 World Championship, with [[Yonny Hern\u00e1ndez]] and [[Mashel Al Naimi]] as riders. The team continued in Moto2 until the conclusion of the [[2013 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2013]] season. In [[2018 Moto2 season|2018]], the team made a significant number of wildcard entries with rider [[Xavi Cardel\u00fas]].\n\n====MotoGP====\nIn {{MGP|2012}} the team changed its name to '''Avintia Racing''', following an alliance between BQR and the Grupo Avintia. The team debuted in the MotoGP class as a Claiming Rule Team using both [[FTR Moto]] and Inmotec frames badged as '''BQR''', powered by [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Motorcycle & Engine|Kawasaki]] engines. The riders were [[Iv\u00e1n Silva (motorcyclist)|Iv\u00e1n Silva]] and [[Yonny Hern\u00e1ndez]]. In {{MGP|2013}} Avintia entered the MotoGP class with Kawasaki-engined FTR frames, fielding two bikes for [[Hiroshi Aoyama]] and [[H\u00e9ctor Barber\u00e1]].\n\nFor the {{MGP|2014}} season Aoyama was replaced by [[Mike Di Meglio]] and the team fielded a new bike badged as the ''Avintia GP14'', reportedly based on the 2007-2009 [[Kawasaki Ninja ZX-RR]] with some input from [[Kawasaki Motors Racing|Kawasaki]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://motomatters.com/analysis/2014/07/16/the_comprehensive_midsummer_motogp_silly.html|title=The Comprehensive Midsummer MotoGP Silly Season Update|first=David|last=Emmett|work=MotoMatters.com|publisher=David Emmett|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motorcyclenews.com/sport/motogp/2014/july/ducati-to-expand-to-six-bike-effort-in-motogp/|title=Ducati to expand to six bike effort in MotoGP|first=Matthew|last=Birt|work=MotorcycleNews.com|publisher=Bauer Consumer Media|date=21 July 2014|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> Following a mid-season agreement between Avintia and [[Ducati]], Barber\u00e1 received an Open-specification [[Ducati Desmosedici]] for the last five rounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.crash.net/motogp/news/209018/1/new-avintia-ducati-ready-for-aragon.html|title=Avintia Ducati unveiled at Aragon|work=Crash.net|publisher=Crash Media Group|date=25 September 2014|accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn {{MGP|2015}} the team entered two Open class [[Ducati Desmosedici|Desmosedici]] GP14 motorcycles, for Barber\u00e1 and Di Meglio. For {{MGP|2016}} Di Meglio was replaced by [[Loris Baz]]. In {{MGP|2017}} the team changed its name to Reale Esponsorama Racing.\n\nIn [[2018 MotoGP season|2018]], [[Tito Rabat]] and [[Xavier Sim\u00e9on]] joined the team. At the [[2018 British motorcycle Grand Prix|British Grand Prix]], Rabat's major crash with [[Franco Morbidelli]] at Stowe corner was a contributing factor in the decision to cancel the race due to unsafe conditions. As a result of the triple fracture he sustained to his right leg, Rabat missed the remaining 7 races of the 2018 season, and was replaced by [[Christophe Ponsson]] and [[Jordi Torres]]. For [[2019 MotoGP season|2019]], Rabat returned and was partnered by Czech rider [[Karel Abraham]]. In [[2020 MotoGP season|2020]], Rabat was retained, this time paired with [[Johann Zarco]].\n\n==== MotoE ====\nAs a satellite team in MotoGP, Avintia was given an entry in the innaugural [[MotoE World Cup]] in [[2019 MotoE season|2019]]. The team achieved 2 wins with [[Eric Granado]] and 2 podiums with their former MotoGP rider [[Xavier Sim\u00e9on]], good for 3rd and 6th place in the championship, respectively. For the [[2020 MotoE season|2020 season]], the team retained Granado and partnered him with their former Moto2 rider, [[Andorra|Andorran]] [[Xavier Cardel\u00fas]]. Subesquently and combined with title sponsorship from Andorran firm Esponsorama, the team decided from 2020 to enter the MotoE team under an Andorran license as opposed to the Spanish license used in all other categories.\n\n==Results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Class\n!scope=\"col\"| Team name\n!scope=\"col\"| Bike\n!scope=\"col\"| Riders\n!scope=\"col\"| Races\n!scope=\"col\"| Wins\n!scope=\"col\"| Podiums\n!scope=\"col\"| [[Pole position|Poles]]\n!scope=\"col\"| [[Fastest lap|F.&nbsp;laps]]\n!scope=\"col\"| Points\n!scope=\"col\"| Pos.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\"| {{MGP|2009}}\n|align=\"left\"| 250cc\n|align=\"left\"| Aeropuerto-Castello-Blusens\n|align=\"left\"| [[Aprilia RSV 250|Aprilia RSA 250]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Alex Deb\u00f3n]]\n| 15 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 101 || 10th\n|-\n|align=\"left\" rowspan=\"3\"| 125cc\n|align=\"left\" rowspan=\"3\"| Blusens-Aprilia\n|align=\"left\" rowspan=\"3\"| [[Aprilia RS125R|Aprilia RSA 125]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Esteve Rabat]]\n| 17 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 37 || 18th\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Scott Redding]]\n| 17 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 50.5 || 15th\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Johnny Rosell]]\n| 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || NC\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"5\"| {{MGP|2010}}\n|align=\"left\" rowspan=\"4\"| Moto2\n|ali