{"title_page": "Murtazali Gadjiev", "text_new": "{{orphan|date=October 2019}}\n\n[[File:Murtazali Gadjiev - Russian-Dagestani archaeologist 2019.jpg|thumb|Murtazali Gadjiev in front of a [[Zoroastrian]] ''[[dakhma]]'' in 2019]]\n'''Murtazali Gadjiev''' ([[Russian language|Russian]]: \u041c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0413\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438\u0435\u0432) is a [[Russia]]n-[[Dagestan]]i archaeologist and scholar. He is the head of the archaeology department of Dagestan Scientific Center of Russian Academy of Science.<ref name=\"D\" >{{cite web|url=https://flnka.ru/digest/10716-derbent-celebrates-2000-years-of-history-and-multiculturalism.html|title=Derbent celebrates 2,000 years of history and multiculturalism|publisher=flnka.ru}}</ref>\n\nProf. Murtazali Gadjiev is specialised in the history of [[Derbent]] (Darband), [[Sasanian]]-era [[Persian Empire|Persian]] presence in [[Caucasus]] and Culture of Caucasian Albania.<ref name=\"B\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/18/world/europe/derbent-as-russias-oldest-city-think-again-moscow-says.html|title=Derbent as Russia\u2019s Oldest City? Think Again, Moscow Says|publisher=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nBorn in 1956 in [[Makhachkala]], Republic of Dagestan and graduated from Daghestan State University (Makhachkala) and Institute of Archaeology, RAS, in Moscow. He has been a professor of 'Field Archaeology' at the Daghestan University in Makhachkala for around 10 years.\n\nMurtazali Gadjjiev is a member of the Editorial board of the ''Journal of Caucasian Archeology'', Tbilisi, and Deputy-Chairman of the Coordinating Committee of The International Conference on the North Caucasus Archaeology ''Krupnovskie chteniya''.<ref name=\"A\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteofhistory.ru/archeologi/|title=\u0413\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438\u0435\u0432, \u041c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438|publisher=instituteofhistory.ru}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ihaednc.academia.edu/GadjievMurtazali Murtazali Gadjiev Academia Page] (English & Russian)\n* [http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/darband-epigraphy-01 Middle Persian Inscriptions in Darband] (Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica)\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gadjiev, Murtazali}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Russian archaeologists]]\n[[Category:People from Dagestan]]\n[[Category:People from Makhachkala]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{orphan|date=October 2019}}\n\n[[File:Murtazali Gadjiev - Russian-Dagestani archaeologist 2019.jpg|thumb|Murtazali Gadjiev in front of a [[Zoroastrian]] ''[[dakhma]]'' in 2019]]\n'''Murtazali Gadjiev''' ([[Russian language|Russian]]: \u041c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0413\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438\u0435\u0432) is a [[Russia]]n-[[Dagestan]]i archaeologist and scholar. He is the head of the archaeology department of Dagestan Scientific Center of Russian Academy of Science.<ref name=\"D\" >{{cite web|url=https://flnka.ru/digest/10716-derbent-celebrates-2000-years-of-history-and-multiculturalism.html|title=Derbent celebrates 2,000 years of history and multiculturalism|publisher=flnka.ru}}</ref>\n\nProf. Murtazali Gadjiev is specialised in the history of [[Derbent]] (Darband), [[Sasanian]]-era [[Persian Empire|Persian]] presence in [[Caucasus]] and Culture of Caucasian Albania.<ref name=\"B\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/18/world/europe/derbent-as-russias-oldest-city-think-again-moscow-says.html|title=Derbent as Russia\u2019s Oldest City? Think Again, Moscow Says|publisher=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nBorn in 1956 in [[Makhachkala]], Republic of Dagestan and graduated from Daghestan State University (Makhachkala) and Institute of Archaeology, RAS, in Moscow. He has been a professor of 'Field Archaeology' at the Daghestan University in Makhachkala for around 10 years.\n\nMurtazali Gadjjiev is a member of the Editorial board of the ''Journal of Caucasian Archeology'', Tbilisi, and Deputy-Chairman of the Coordinating Committee of The International Conference on the North Caucasus Archaeology ''Krupnovskie chteniya''.<ref name=\"A\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteofhistory.ru/archeologi/|title=\u0413\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438\u0435\u0432, \u041c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438|publisher=instituteofhistory.ru}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ihaednc.academia.edu/GadjievMurtazali Murtazali Gadjiev Academia Page] (English & Russian)\n* [http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/darband-epigraphy-01 Middle Persian Inscriptions in Darband] (Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gadjiev, Murtazali}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Russian archaeologists]]\n[[Category:People from Dagestan]]\n[[Category:People from Makhachkala]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murtazali_Gadjiev"}
{"title_page": "Baltimore", "text_new": "{{Short description|Largest city in Maryland, United States}}\n{{about|the city in Maryland|the surrounding county|Baltimore County, Maryland}}\n{{redirect|Baltimore City|other uses|Baltimore (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Baltimore, Maryland\n| official_name                   = City of Baltimore\n| settlement_type                 = [[Independent city (United States)|Independent city]]\n| image_skyline                   = BaltimoreC12.png\n| imagesize                       =\n| image_caption                   = [[Downtown Baltimore|Downtown]], [[Emerson Bromo-Seltzer Tower]], [[Pennsylvania Station (Baltimore)|Pennsylvania Station]], [[M&T Bank Stadium]], [[Inner Harbor]] and the [[National Aquarium (Baltimore)|National Aquarium]] in Baltimore, [[Baltimore City Hall]], [[Washington Monument, Baltimore|Washington Monument]]\n| image_flag                      = Flag of Baltimore City.svg\n| image_seal                      = Seal of Baltimore, Maryland.png\n| nickname                        = Charm City;<ref name=nicknames>{{cite web |url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/business/511672/baltimores_new_bait_the_city_is_about_to_unveil_a/index.html\n|title=Baltimore's New Bait: The City is About to Unveil a New Slogan, 'Get In On It,' Meant to Intrigue Visitors |access-date=November 28, 2008 |last=Donovan |first=Doug |date=May 20, 2006|work=The Baltimore Sun|via=RedOrbit<!--present in archive.org-->}}</ref> B'more;<ref name=nicknames2>{{Cite news |last=Kane|first=Gregory |author-link=Gregory Kane (journalist) | url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/article/37312 | work=[[The Washington Examiner]] | title=Dispatch from Bodymore, Murderland | date=June 15, 2009<!--present in archive.is-->}}</ref>\n| motto                           = \"The Greatest City in America\",<ref name=nicknames /> \"Get in on it.\",<re