{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{current related||2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Globalize|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:Closed library - Island Bay.jpg|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Announcement posted in the door of a [[public library]] in [[Island Bay, New Zealand]] that it is closed due to the pandemic, and will waive all [[Late fees|late return fees]].]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] had a sudden and substantial impact on the [[performing arts]] and cultural heritage ([[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAM]]) sectors. The global health crisis and the uncertainly resulting from it profoundly affected organisations' operations as well as individuals \u2013 both employed and independent \u2013 across the sector. Arts and culture sector organisations attempted to uphold their (often publicly funded) mission to provide access to cultural heritage to the community; maintain the safety of their employees, collections, and the public; while reacting to the unexpected change in their [[business model]] with an unknown end.\n\nBy March 2020, across the world most cultural institutions had been indefinitely closed (or at least with their services radically curtailed) exhibitions, events and performances cancelled or postponed. In response there were intensive efforts to provide alternative services through digital platforms, to maintain essential activities with minimal revenue, and simultaneously an awareness that there would be many new [[creative works]] which had been inspired by the event.\n\nMany individuals across the sector would temporarily or permanently lose contracts or employment with varying degrees of warning and financial assistance available. Equally, [[financial stimulus]] from governments and charities for artists, would provide greatly differing levels of support depending on the sector and the country. The public demand for cultural activities was expected to return, but in at an unknown time and with the assumption that different kinds of experiences would be popular.\n\n==Closures== \nThrough the first months of 2020, arts and culture sector organisations around the world progressively restricted their public activities and closed completely due to the coronavirus pandemic. Starting with China, and East Asia, by mid-to-late March most organisations worldwide had either closed voluntarily or by government mandate. This included libraries,<ref name=\"IFLA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ifla.org/covid-19-and-libraries|title=COVID-19 and the Global Library Field|publisher=[[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions|IFLA]]|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> museums,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/coronavirus-museum-closures-worldwide-1202680933/|title=See a List of Coronavirus-Related Closures at Museums Around the World|last=Solomon|first=Claire Selvin,Tessa|last2=Selvin|first2=Claire|date=2020-03-12|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26|last3=Solomon|first3=Tessa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LNCETkPjgcNdmybrwE5g2JEK4KpIfhKThnws1QqgjqE/mobilebasic|title=Museum Responses - COVID-19|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> theatre and stage productions,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2020/mar/13/coronavirus-culture-arts-films-gigs-festivals-cancellations|title=Coronavirus and culture \u2013 a list of major cancellations|date=2020-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and arts festivals.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2020, dates for re-opening and expectations for when cultural organisation can fully \"return to normal\" are unknown for most of the world. Survey data from March in the USA indicated that, when museums were permitted to reopen, the public \"intent to visit\" metric for cultural activities should be unchanged overall from prior to the pandemic \u2013 but with a shifted preference for the ''kind'' of activity. Data indicated there would be a decreased willingness for attendance of activities in confined spaces, large immobile groups (such as cinemas), or tactile activities; with an increase in interest for activities outdoors or with large spaces (such as zoos and botanic gardens).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/25/how-is-covid-19-impacting-likelihood-to-attend-different-cultural-entities-data/|title=Post-Pandemic, Which Cultural Entity Types Are People More Likely to Revisit? (DATA)|date=2020-03-25|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/23/weekly-data-update-how-covid-19-is-impacting-intentions-to-visit-cultural-entities-march-23-2020/|title=DATA UPDATE: How COVID-19 is Impacting Intentions to Visit Cultural Entities - March 23, 2020|date=2020-03-23|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The most commonly cited reasons for the public to \"feel safe\" in returning would be: the availability of a [[COVID-19 vaccine|vaccine]], governments lifting travel restrictions, knowing that other people had visited, whether the activity/institution was outdoors, and the provision of [[hand sanitiser]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/04/01/what-will-make-people-feel-safe-attending-a-cultural-entity-again-data/|title=What Will Make People Feel Safe Attending a Cultural Entity Again? (DATA)|date=2020-04-01|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nBy early April at least one museum had announced its permanent closure, with more expected to follow.\n\n''The following is a list of notable closures, announcements and policies affecting the cultural sector.<br>For comprehensive lists:''\n{{See also|List of public venues and institutions closed during the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}} \n{{See also|List of events affected by the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n'''Africa'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Egypt}}. From March 23 until March 31, 2020 all museums and archaeological sites in Egypt were closed to the public for sterilization and disinfection. During this period a programme to raise the awareness of the sites and museums\u2019 employees on ways of prevention and protection against the virus took place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cairoscene.com/Buzz/Egypt-to-Close-All-Museums-and-Archaeological-Sites|title= Egypt to close all museums and archaeological sites}}</ref>\n\n'''Asia'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flagicon|China}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]]. On 23 January 2020 all museums were closed throughout mainland China, As the first country for the virus to spread, China was also the first to close its GLAMs.<ref name=\":0\" /> By Mid-March Chinese institutions had slowly and cautiously begun to allow various public activities to be restored with the [[Shanghai Museum]] and the [[Power Station of Art]] (also in Shanghai) reopening on the 13th. Both had restricted visitor numbers and the latter noted that, \u201cWe have also prepared a temporary quarantine area on every floor in case of any emergencies. All visitors must have their temperature taken, as well as present their ID card and registered health code, before entering.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/china-japan-south-korea-museums-reopen-coronavirus-1202680994/|title=Museums in China, South Korea, Japan Begin to Reopen After Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Solomon|first=Tessa|last2=Solomon|first2=Tessa|date=2020-03-13|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Some other private galleries in China had begun to open, as had some institutions in South Korea and Japan with limited service (such as by private tour only). By the end of the month 40% of mainland China's tourism attractions had reopened yet most art venues remained closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/china-south-korea-and-japan-start-to-reopen-museums|title=China, South Korea and Japan start to reopen museums after strict coronavirus lockdown|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Hong Kong}}. Following the mainland, Hong Kong closed its museums five days later.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Japan}}. On 28 February Japan announced all museums would be closed \"until 17 March\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in|Qatar}}. Qatar museums run by the state closed on 12 March. A forthcoming collaborative show on Picasso's Studio's due to be held by the [[Fire Station (gallery)|Fire Station]] and [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso]] has been indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |South Korea}}. On 23 February, one month after mainland China, South Korea closed all museums \"until further notice\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Europe'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts -->\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Austria}}. All federal public museums were closed by directors in response to government precautionary measures banning large events and arrivals from Italy. The [[Albertina Modern]] museum was supposed to open on 13 March but this opening was indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Belgium}}. All cultural activities regardless of size were banned by the government from 14 March, which involved the closure of the [[Jan van Eyck]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Ghent]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. Weeks earlier than French government regulations required it, staff of [[The Louvre]] \"almost unanimously\" voted to force the closure of the museum on the 1st of March, due to concerns for their own health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51697644|title=Staff force Louvre closure over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> It closed for three days, reopened,<ref>{{cite web|title=Coronavirus: Louvre museum in Paris reopens after staff walkout|url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20200301/frances-louvre-museum-closed-due-to-virus-fears|website=www.thelocal.fr|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> accepted only visitors with pre-booked tickets from the 9th,<ref name=\":0\" /> then closed definitively on the 13th by government mandate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200313-france-s-louvre-museum-and-versailles-palace-to-shut-over-coronavirus-crisis|title=Louvre, Versailles and Eiffel Tower close over coronavirus crisis|date=2020-03-13|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Reconstruction of the [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame cathedral]] following [[Notre-Dame de Paris fire|the 2019 fire]] was also halted because of worker security.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. On 16 March 2020, the German chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] announced in a press conference that the government and [[minister-president]]s had together agreed upon guidelines to limit social contacts in public spaces. Theatres, opera houses, concert halls, museums, exhibition spaces, cinemas, amusement parks and zoos needed to close.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/leitlinien-bund-laender-1731000|title=Leitlinien gegen Ausbreitung des Coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|website=Die Bundesregierung|language=de|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. As the worst hit country in Europe during February and March, national closures were announced on the 23rd of February with an initial reopening date of 1 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/la-cultura-chiusa-tempi-coronavirus-ACNKCpLB|title=La cultura chiusa ai tempi del coronavirus|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Museums outside the \"red zone\" of highly infected areas in the North were then permitted to re-open as long as visitors stayed 1 meter apart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/italian-museums-reopen-following-government-green-light|title=Coronavirus: Louvre closes while Italian museums reopen following government green light|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> this was later rescinded and all institution were closed until at least 3 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/rome-s-blockbuster-raphael-exhibition-closes|title=Coronavirus in Italy: Ai Weiwei criticised for 'insensitive' pasta meme and Raphael blockbuster closes|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The closure forced the indefinite postponement of the forthcoming \u201cmega-exhibition\u201d of [[Raphael]] to be held at the [[Scuderie del Quirinale]] in Rome. Originally timed to coincide with the 500th anniversary of the [[Renaissance art|Renaissance painter's]] death, it was to be the largest number of Raphaels ever displayed together.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Vatican City}}. The [[Vatican Museums]] closed in accordance with the policies of Italy.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Netherlands}}. On 12 March, Amsterdam's [[Rijksmuseum]] and [[Van Gogh Museum]] announced they would close until at least the end of that month.<ref name=\":0\" /> The following day, having previously announced the reading room and exhibition would remain open, the [[Nationaal Archief|National Archives]] announced their complete closure until April 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaalarchief.nl/beleven/nieuws/studiezaal-en-tentoonstelling-nationaal-archief-tijdelijk-gesloten|title=Studiezaal en tentoonstelling Nationaal Archief tijdelijk gesloten|website=Nationaal Archief|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>  On 30 March, the painting ''[[The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen]]'' (1884) by [[Vincent van Gogh]] was stolen from the [[Singer Laren|Singer Laren museum]] while the museum was closed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/i-m-absolutely-livid-van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-museum-during-pandemic-20200331-p54fgd.html|title='I'm absolutely livid': Van Gogh painting stolen from museum during pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Poland}}. On 11 March a regional government \"recommendation\" was made that all cultural venues in the [[Tricity, Poland|tricity]] area be closed for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kultura.trojmiasto.pl/Teatry-odwolane-imprezy-spektakle-koronawirus-w-Trojmiescie-n143084.html|title=Teatry zamkni\u0119te przynajmniej na 2 tygodnie|date=2020-03-10|website=trojmiasto.pl|language=pl|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Museums, including the [[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]], and other cultural venues such as theatres and cinemas were then closed by the national government with an initial re-opening date of 25 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Russia}}. The [[Garage Museum of Contemporary Art]] was one of the first to announce its closure from 14 March. Many [[Moscow]] museums announced closures in response to the mayor's ban on gatherings of 50 people or more on 17 March, and late that day the Russian culture ministry ordered the suspension of all public activities by federal and regional institutions, which resulted in many more closures from 18 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Spain}}. On 11 March, publicly owned museums in Madrid, including [[The Prado]], were closed indefinitely.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Sagrada Fam\u00edlia]] indefinitely suspended construction works and closed the monument to visitors on 13 March and the [[Guggenheim Museum Bilbao]] closed on 14 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. On 18 March, the Swedish network and cooperation organisation for public museums of national interest, ''Centralmuseernas samarbetsr\u00e5d'', recommended all their 13 members to close their public venues if the risk for transmission of the virus was assessed as high in their respective regions. Only two of them stayed open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigesmuseer.se/nyheter/2020/03/cms-rekommenderar-stangning-av-centralmuseer-i-omraden-med-hog-smittspridning/|title=CMS rekommenderar st\u00e4ngning av centralmuseer i omr\u00e5den med h\u00f6g smittspridning|date=2020-03-18|website=Sveriges museer|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. The earliest closures of cultural institutions in the UK were announced from 13 March by [[Wellcome Collection]], [[South London Gallery]], the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]], [[The Photographers' Gallery]] and [[Amgueddfa Cymru \u2013 National Museum Wales|Amgueddfa Cymru]].<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|last=McGivern|first=Hannah|last2=Kenney|first2=Nancy|date=14 March 2020|website=The Art Newspaper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Many other organisations announced closures on the 17 and 18 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/london-museums-galleries-exhibitions-closed-coronavirus-a4389351.html|title=The London galleries and museums that are closed due to coronavirus|last=Paskett|first=Zoe|date=17 March 2020|website=Evening Standard|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51928526|title=Tate, V&A and Natural History Museum to close|date=2020-03-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] closed all ticketed properties by 20 March but aimed to keep gardens and parklands open, free of charge so that people could access the open space whilst social distancing.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe planned major exhibition at the [[National Gallery]] in London of [[Artemisia Gentileschi]], set to open on April 4, was postponed for an indeterminate time due not only to the gallery's closure but also the inability of artworks on loan from Italy and America being unable to fly during the global shutdown in air traffic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jones|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/16/artemisia-gentileschi-national-gallery-exhibition-postponed-coronavirus|title=With coronavirus, the curse of Artemisia Gentileschi strikes again|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The [[Glasgow International]] 2020 arts festival was posponed until 2021.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n'''North America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A \"flurry\" of museums in New York, Boston and Washington all announced their closure on March 12, led by the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and coinciding with the New York Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] declaring a city wide emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/metropolitan-museum-of-art-to-shut-down-because-of-coronavirus|title=Led by Metropolitan Museum of Art, a flurry of US museums say they are shutting down because of coronavirus|last=Kenny|first=Nancy|date=2020-03-12|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[The Broadway League]] announced on the same day that all [[Broadway theatres]] would cease performances for at least a month, even though New York State governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] had at the time allowed them to continue at 50% capacity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/health/broadway-coronavirus-update/index.html|title=Broadway theaters to suspend all performances because of coronavirus|author1=Taylor Romine |author2=Eric Levenson |author3=Javi Morgado|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On March 17, two days before the [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|first State to declare a \"stay at home\" order]], the [[American Library Association]] \"strongly recommended\" that all academic, public, and school libraries close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/news/press-releases/2020/03/ala-executive-board-recommends-closing-libraries-public|title=ALA Executive Board recommends closing libraries to public|last=|first=|date=2020-03-17|website=|publisher=[[American Library Association]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n'''Oceania'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. Beginning from the second week of March Australian institutions began announcing reduced services, and then complete closures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wragge.github.io/closed-glams-covid19/|title=Australian GLAMs and COVID-19|website=closed-glams-covid19|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Opera Australia]] announced it would close on the 15th.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://operawire.com/opera-australia-cancels-performances-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Opera Australia Cancels Performances Due to Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|website=Opera Wire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On the 24th the national closure of all cultural institutions was required.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |New Zealand}}. New Zealand implemented a policy on March 23 that all institutions would be closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndf.org.nz/covid19-and-nz-glams|title=COVID-19 and NZ GLAMs|website=National Digital Forum|language=en-NZ|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]] closed from 6pm March 20.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Campbell|first=Georgina|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318548|title=Coronavirus: Te Papa museum to close for two weeks|date=20 March 2020|work=New Zealand Herald|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Auckland War Memorial Museum]] announced that it would close from March 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/service-pages/alerts/covid-19?utm_source=wordfly&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=TemporaryMuseumClosure&utm_content=version_A|title=Auckland Museum is temporarily closed}}</ref>\n\n'''South America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Argentina}}. All the museums, cultural activities and gatherings were cancelled in the city of Buenos Aires on the 12th of March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/cultura/coronavirus-argentina-disponen-cierre-temporario-museos-ciudad_0_Hgfv9C32.html|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: disponen el cierre temporario de todos los museos de la Ciudad|last=|website=www.clarin.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> National libraries continue to offer means of contact through the main educational website of the Ministry of Education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.educ.ar/recursos/151053/bibliotecas-en-casa-en-seguimos-conectados?from=150858&fbclid=IwAR3S3KjeZavdRV6gjOCfJxVUz6Xu5L0Eqfep7SBTT5l1RrOOKvuHQDML0tY|title=#BibliotecasEnCasa en Seguimos Educando - Educ.ar|website=www.educ.ar|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Brazil}}. Museums which have closed{{when|date=March 2020}} in Brazil include the Museum of Art of S\u00e3o Paulo Assis Chateaubriand, the Pinacoteca, the Ita\u00fa Cultural, the Museum of Contemporary Art of the University of S\u00e3o Paulo, the Institute Tomie Ohtake, the Institute Moreira Salles, and the Museum of Tomorrow in Rio de Janeiro and the Instituto Inhotim contemporary art centre in Brumadinho.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Permanent closure ===\n{{Incomplete list|date=April 2020}}\nThe first cultural institution to announced its permanent closure as a result of the pandemic was [[Indianapolis Contemporary]], a contemporary art museum founded in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/arts/2020/04/03/indianapolis-contemporary-art-museum-shuts-down-coronavirus/5115668002/|title=Indianapolis Contemporary art museum shuts down, citing economic damage from coronavirus|last=Bongiovanni|first=Domenica|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> An announcement from its board on April 3, 2020 stated that \"We have concluded our operations are not sustainable. We are not alone as other arts institutions struggle in this crisis.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indcontemporary.org/press-release/ic-to-close|title=I/C Board Announces Plans To Close|website=Indianapolis Contemporary|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nFacing at least several weeks of closure of their buildings and publicly-accessible spaces, many cultural sector organisations and individual artists turned to digital activities as a way to continue fulfilling their organisational mission and obtain or retain an audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@kajsahartig/museums-delivering-value-online-some-thoughts-during-the-covid-19-crisis-193fc0a58d22|title=Museums delivering value online \u2014 some thoughts during the Covid-19 crisis|last=Hartig|first=Kajsa|date=2020-03-29|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Farago|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/arts/design/coronavirus-digital-artists.html|title=The Merry-Go-Round Stopped. What Sort of Art Will Emerge?|date=2020-03-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For example, the [[BBC]] launched a \"virtual festival of the arts\" called ''Culture in quarantine''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/culture-in-quarantine|title=BBC - BBC Arts announces new programmes for Culture In Quarantine - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Sydney Biennale]] became the first international [[arts festival]] to go entirely digital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/the-biennale-of-sydney-is-moving-online-1811871|title=Dawn of the Online Biennial Era? The Biennale of Sydney Becomes the First Major International Art Show to Go Virtual|last=Rea|first=Naomi|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Artnet]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\nHaving been the first country to enforce quarantine upon its population, museums in China were also the first to provide new digital services (primarily for a domestic audience, but to a lesser extent also internationally). In January the [[National Cultural Heritage Administration]] (NCHA) said they would \"encourage cultural heritage museums and institutions around the country to utilise existing digital resources and launch online exhibitions as appropriate, providing the public with safe and convenient online services.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/chinas-museums-offer-online-exhibitions-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ar-BBZEOr6|title=China's museums offer online exhibitions amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncha.gov.cn/art/2020/1/28/art_722_158541.html|title=\u5173\u4e8e\u5411\"\u535a\u7269\u9986\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5e73\u53f0\"\u63d0\u4f9b\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5185\u5bb9\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u5021\u8bae\u4e66|website=www.ncha.gov.cn|publisher=[[National Cultural Heritage Administration]]|language=zh|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMany institutions turned to their existing [[social media]] presences to engage their audience online. Quickly, the [[Twitter|Twitter hashtag]] #MuseumFromHome became particularly popular for museums sharing their content in innovative ways. Various institutions were singled out for particular praise by industry analysts for their successful social media content strategy during the shutdown. These included the [[Shedd Aquarium]] in Chicago for filming their penguins visiting other animals; the [[Royal Academy]] in London for asking its followers to draw their own artworks; and the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in Oklahoma for providing an authentic and unusual 'voice' to their social media - from their security guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/museum-social-media-entertains-during-the-covid-19-crisis/|title=Museum Social Media Entertains During the COVID-19 Crisis|date=2020-03-19|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boredpanda.com/national-cowboy-museum-head-of-security-twitter/|title=Cowboy Museum Puts Their Head Of Security In Charge Of Their Twitter, And His Tweets Are Hilariously Wholesome|website=Bored Panda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Individual actors and musicians offered [[impromptu]] performances via their personal accounts from their homes \u2013 singing [[Cover version|covers]], performing live book or [[poetry readings]], or creatively live-streaming themselves doing both normal and unusual activities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stubbins|first=Sinead|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-cabin-fever-the-best-celebrities-to-follow-from-robbie-williams-to-florence-pugh|title=Coronavirus cabin fever: the best celebrities to follow, from Robbie Williams to Florence Pugh|date=2020-03-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nVarious [[internet journalism]] and [[Industry association]]s published lists of new digitally-accessible arts and culture content for their country. Including Argentina,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buenosaires.gob.ar/culturaencasa|title=Cultura en casa|website=Buenos Aires Ciudad - Gobierno de la Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ozglam.info/s/updates/page/welcome|title=Australian GLAM updates|website=ozglam.info|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irishmuseums.org/text-pages/irishmuseumsonline-content-and-resources|title=#IrishMuseumsOnline: content and resources|website=Irish Museums Association|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalist.it/arti/2020/03/13/musei-chiusi-per-coronavirus-cosa-offrono-sul-web-e-social-mentre-iorestoacasa-2054444.html|title=Musei chiusi per Coronavirus: cosa offrono sul web e social mentre #iorestoacasa|website=Globalist|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2020/03/18/coronavirus-dal-louvre-agli-uffizi-i-musei-chiusi-ora-si-visitano-online-cineteche-teatri-e-biblioteche-cosi-la-cultura-arriva-direttamente-a-casa/5739782/|title=Coronavirus, dal Louvre agli Uffizi, i musei chiusi ora si visitano online. Cinema, teatri e biblioteche: cos\u00ec la cultura arriva direttamente a casa|date=2020-03-18|website=Il Fatto Quotidiano|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/19032020-how-digital-platforms-be-used-to-support-musems-during-covid-19-crisis|title=How can digital platforms help museums connect to audiences during Covid-19 emergency|publisher=[[Museums Association]]|website=www.museumsassociation.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kidsinmuseums.org.uk/2020/03/10-museum-activities-to-keep-children-entertained/|title=10 museum activities to keep children entertained|date=2020-03-23|website=Kids in Museums|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===By sector===\n====[[Public aquarium|Aquaria]] and [[zoo]]s====\nThe impact of the pandemic has been a uniquely serious crisis for some zoos \u2013 with reduced revenues for the operators but also reduced opportunities for [[stimulation]] for \"...the most intelligent and social animals \u2013 including [[gorillas]], [[kea]], [[otters]] and [[meerkats]]\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=Roy|first=Eleanor Ainge|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/02/new-zealand-zoos-strive-to-entertain-lonely-inhabitants-amid-lockdown|title=Animal tragic: New Zealand zoos strive to entertain lonely inhabitants amid lockdown|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In order to maintain physical distancing but also still care for the animals, some zookeepers (classed as \"[[Essential worker|essential workers]]\") began living on-site at certain zoos.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mohdin|first=Aamna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/30/the-animals-arent-pleased-how-shut-uk-zoos-are-coping-under-coronavirus-lockdown|title='The animals aren't pleased': UK zoos under coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-03-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Animals who would normally have a regular scheduled public feeding, petting, or performance for zoo visitors were reported to be still \"keeping their appointments\" and noticing that \"omething odd is upI\".<ref name=\":6\" /> n response to the absence of visitors, several institutions launched new [[webcams]] and [[livestreams]] of their animal habitats as well as feeding sessions. In one case, penguins were taken by their [[zookeeper|keepers]] to other animal enclosures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Padilla|first=Mariel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/us/coronavirus-zoos-webcams.html|title=Stuck at Home, You Can Still Explore the Zoo or Aquarium. Some Penguins Could, Too.|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Vigdor|first2=Neil|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/travel/story/2020-03-20/virtual-touring|title=Watching animals helps. A lot. Here are the best webcams|date=2020-03-20|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nDue to the sudden collapse in international travel, the [[wildlife tourism]] sector risks the potential starvation of the animals. Due to the lack of tourists paying for food more than 1,000 [[Elephants in Thailand]] risk starvation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hatton|first=Celia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52110551|title=Thai elephants face starvation as tourism plummets|date=2020-03-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Paddock|first=Richard C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/coronavirus-thailand-elephants.html|title=As Tourism Plummets in Thailand, Elephants Are Out of Work, Too|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-06|last2=Suhartono|first2=Muktita|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Dean|first3=Adam}}</ref> A \"brawl\" of hundreds of [[Long-tailed macaque]] broke out in the streets of [[Lopburi]], Thailand (known as \"monkey city\"), as the animals \u2013 normally sustained by scraps by tourists \u2013 fought for food.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ratcliffe|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/13/fighting-monkeys-highlight-effect-of-coronavirus-on-thailand-tourism|title=Mass monkey brawl highlights coronavirus effect on Thailand tourism|date=2020-03-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In countries wildlife tourism represents a significant portion of employment (such as Tanzania and Namibia), there is concern that a loss of jobs related to conservation will see a rise in [[poaching]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-lockdown-conservation/|title=The Coronavirus Lockdown Is a Threat for Many Animals, Not a Blessing|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\nNadia, a tiger at the [[Bronx Zoo]] in New York, tested positive for COVID-19 in the first week of April after developing a \"dry cough\" after having been infected via an asymptomatic zookeeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/us/tiger-coronavirus-new-york-trnd/index.html|title=A tiger at the Bronx Zoo tests positive for coronavirus|first=Alaa |last=Elassar|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> This was the first known case of a wild animal having been infected via a human (two domestic dogs and a cat had previously been diagnosed).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/04/tiger-coronavirus-covid19-positive-test-bronx-zoo/|title=Tiger tests positive for coronavirus at Bronx Zoo, first known case in the world|date=2020-04-05|website=Animals|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n====[[Film industry|Cinema]] and [[Television industry|television]]====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|l1=Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television|l2=on television}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n\nThe production and release schedule of many films was suspended or delayed, with some awards ceremonies and festivals being cancelled entirely. March 2020 estimates were of approximately $5b losses for the industry.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shoard|first=Catherine|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/cinema-coronavirus-projected-5bn-loss|title=Cinema bullish in the face of coronavirus despite projected $5bn loss|date=2020-03-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Examples of adaptations included the early [[Home video|home media]] release ([[Frozen II|''Frozen II'']]), [[Theatrical release|theatrical releases]] being cancelled entirely (''[[Lost in Russia]]''), and online premieres ([[Enter the Fat Dragon (2020 film)|''Enter the Fat Dragon'']]). \n\nSimilarly, the [[television industry]] saw production halted on many [[Scripted television|scripted]] and [[unscripted television|unscripted]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} shows. This included series which had been running uninterrupted for the proceeding several decades, including: [[The Bold and the Beautiful]] (season 34), [[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]] (season 34), [[Days of Our Lives]] (season 55), [[Home and Away]] (season 33), [[Saturday Night Live]] (season 45), and [[The Young and the Restless]] (season 47). Some shows continue with production but without their normal [[studio audience]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-tv-shows-production-delayed-1202881997/|title=Coronavirus: TV Shows That Have Halted Or Delayed Production Amid Outbreak|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|last2=Pedersen|first2=Erik|date=2020-03-16|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In parallel to the suspension of entertainment content production, there was a marked increase in the use of [[video streaming]] services for entertainment (as well as [[videoconferencing]] services such as [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] for work and education) due to the massive increase of people staying at home \u2013 causing unprecedented strain on global [[internet infrastructure]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-can-the-internet-handle-unprecedented-surge-in-traffic.html|title=The internet is under huge strain because of the coronavirus. Experts say it can cope \u2014 for now|last=Browne|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-27|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In response, [[Netflix]] and [[YouTube]] both decreased the default video quality to [[standard definition]], [[Disney+]] delayed its launch in France, and [[Xbox]] requested developers to schedule software updates at times of lower network congestion.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kang|first=Cecilia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/business/coronavirus-internet-traffic-speed.html|title=Surging Traffic Is Slowing Down Our Internet|date=2020-03-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|last2=Alba|first2=Davey|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Satariano|first3=Adam}}</ref>\n\nDue to the global cancellation of [[professional sports]], the loss of advertising revenue and broadcast rights derived from the [[broadcasting of sports events]] is expected to threaten the financial viability of many competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/20/sports-broadcast-impact-coronavirus/|title=For the sports-entertainment business, coronavirus is taking a huge toll|last=Zeitchik|first=Steven|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n====[[Libraries]]====\nLibraries faced different situations, from maintaining a full service with some restrictions, through providing minimal services, to complete closure. Following publications from in [[The New England Journal of Medicine]], and the [[Journal of Hospital Infection]], the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]] in the United States suggesting that the risk of coronavirus transmission from paper was low. In the light of this, the [[International Federation of Library Associations]] noted that some libraries had imposed a wait period before handling returned books, while others have made it clear that no-one is expected to return borrowed books until things return to normal.<ref name=\"IFLA\" /> Some libraries  stopped programmes which would see people spend longer periods together. Others closed public reading rooms or only allow people to collect books on appointment, either inside or outside of the building \u2013 for example setting up tables, with a [[drive-through]], or book delivery service to especially vulnerable community groups.<ref name=\"IFLA\" />\n\nLibraries of different sizes and purposes around the world worked to provide access to collections and services remotely. For example, the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]] organised [[virtual exhibition]]s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fantasy.bnf.fr/fr|title=Fantasy, retour aux sources|website=Fantasy, retour aux sources|language=fr|publisher=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> the Granby library in [[Quebec City|Quebec]] highlighted content focused on learning new skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lavoixdelest.ca/actualites/covid-19/a-un-clic-de-1300-cours-en-ligne-23003711130c1556504efdc64b1422d2|title=\u00c0 un clic de 1300 cours en ligne|date=2020-03-28|website=La Voix de l\u2019Est|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> and the [[National library of Israel]] announced it would provide free audiobooks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/national-library-offers-free-audiobooks-amid-coronavirus-closures-621664|title=National Library offers free audiobooks amid coronavirus closures|website=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Many [[public libraries]] are promoting \"online storytimes\". There have also been major efforts to boost access to [[eBooks]]: by increasing the number of eBooks that people can borrow at any given time, by reassigning budgets to pay for electronic content,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2020/03/20/demand-e-books-rises-area-libraries|title=Demand For E-books Rises At Area Libraries|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"IFLA\" /> On March 24 the [[Internet Archive]] announced the creation of a \"National Emergency Library\" whereby it suspended the waitlists on 1.4m ebooks from their lending library \u2013 books that are not in the [[Public domain in the United States|Public domain in the USA]] \u2013 in order to ensure uninterrupted access to works books for educators and students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.archive.org/2020/03/24/announcing-a-national-emergency-library-to-provide-digitized-books-to-students-and-the-public/|title=Announcing a National Emergency Library to Provide Digitized Books to Students and the Public|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Internet Archive Blogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/internet-archive-offers-thousands-of-copyrighted-books-for-free-online/|title=Internet Archive offers 1.4 million copyrighted books for free online|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=2020-03-28|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The announcement strongly criticised by the [[publishing industry]].<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe Library of the [[National Congress of Argentina]] created activities including public readings and delivery of selected artworks through [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/cultura/2020/03/18/biblioteca-del-congreso-todas-las-actividades-online-durante-la-pandemia-del-coronavirus/|title=Biblioteca del Congreso: todas las actividades online durante la pandemia del coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n====[[Museums]]====\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cThis year, the paint has more time to dry.\u201d<br> \nA statement from the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] announcing a delay to the [[Archibald Prize]] portraiture exhibition until after the health crisis, \"when art will be needed more than ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/paint-has-more-time-to-dry-archibald-prize-delayed-20200321-p54ck2.html|title='Paint has more time to dry': Archibald Prize delayed|date=21 March 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMany websites were rapidly updated to focus on digital resources. In mid-March the [[Museum Computer Network]] published an extensive \"Guide to Virtual Museum Resources, E-Learning, and Online Collections\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcn.edu/a-guide-to-virtual-museum-resources/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Virtual Museum Resources|date=2020-03-15|website=MCN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Lists also were published of fine-art museums with existing interactive services (notably those already \"partners\" of [[Google Arts & Culture]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/547919/2500-virtual-museum-tours-google-arts-culture/|title=2,500 Museums You Can Now Visit Virtually|date=2020-03-16|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philbrook Museum of Art]]'s rapid relaunch their website in late-March \u2013 in order \"for us all to spend some time practicing social distancing and experiencing the #MuseumFromHome\" \u2013 was described as a model example of how an institution could \"Reorganise, Reuse and Rethink\" its activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/reorganise-reuse-get-creative-and-relaunch-lessons-from-philbrook/|title=Reorganise, Reuse, Rethink and Relaunch - Lessons from Philbrook|date=2020-03-21|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Other specific examples included [[Europeana]] publishing a digital gallery of images relating to the theme of [[handwashing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.europeana.eu/en/galleries/washing-your-hands|title=Washing your hands|website=www.europeana.eu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Museum of New Zealand]] publishing a \"little page of calm\" (a reference to the 1997 bestselling book ''[[Little book of calm]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tepapa.govt.nz/discover-collections/read-watch-play/little-page-calm|title=The little page of calm|date=2020-03-16|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa, Wellington, NZ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nAmerican art museum [[Indianapolis Contemporary]] has announced permanent closure as a result of the financial strain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indcontemporary.org/press-release/ic-to-close |title=I/C Board Announces Plans To Close \u2014 Indianapolis Contemporary |publisher=Indcontemporary.org |date=2020-02-04 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n====[[Music]]====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the music industry}}\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cIt is very hard financially and if you have lost the momentum you have built up over time,\" ... But this is also an ideal time for artists to do what it is they are supposed to be doing: create art.\"<br>Musician and performer, [[Tim Minchin]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cooper|first=Nathanael|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/for-musicians-collapse-of-touring-industry-opens-door-to-creativity-20200403-p54gpx.html|title=For musicians, collapse of touring industry opens door to creativity|date=5 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\nMany musicians delayed the releases of [[Album|albums]] due to the pandemic (including [[Lady Gaga]] and [[Willie Nelson]]),<ref name=\"rstone1\">{{cite web |last1=Leight |first1=Elias |title=They Were Going to Be Spring's Biggest Albums -- Until COVID-19 Hit |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/album-delays-caused-by-covid-19-973870/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> some moved up the release dates of their upcoming albums (including [[Dua Lipa]] and [[Sufjan Stevens]]),<ref name=\"sgum1\">{{cite web |last1=Rettig |first1=James |title=HAIM, Dua Lipa, Willie Nelson, & Sufjan Stevens Among Artists Moving Album Release Dates Amid Pandemic |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077667/dua-lipa-willie-nelson-sufjan-stevens-among-artists-moving-album-release-dates-amid-pandemic/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> and others (including [[Nine Inch Nails]] and [[Phish]]) released new albums with little or no notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farokhmanesh |first1=Megan |title=Nine Inch Nails just released two new albums for free |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/26/21195266/nine-inch-nails-new-albums-just-ghosts-v-vi-free-download |website=The Verge |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Phish to Debut New Album 'Sigma Oasis' During April 1st Livestream |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/phish-new-album-sigma-oasis-976437/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> In the middle of March, [[Bob Dylan]] released a single 17 minute new song called \"[[Murder Most Foul (song)|Murder Most Foul]]\", his first piece of original material in eight years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McFadyen|first=Matthew|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/murder-most-foul-bob-dylan-s-surprise-song-for-the-viral-age-20200330-p54f8z.html|title=Murder Most Foul: Bob Dylan's surprise song for the viral age|date=30 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020 Eurovision Song Contest]], set to take place in May in [[Rotterdam]], [[Netherlands]], was canceled by the [[European Broadcasting Union]] in March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official EBU statement & FAQ on Eurovision 2020 cancellation |url=https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation |website=Eurovision.tv |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> This marked the first time the annual contest had not taken place since its first installment in 1956.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eurovision Song Contest Canceled Because of Coronavirus |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eurovision-song-contest-cancelled-because-coronavirus-1282660 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIndividually and collectively, [[musicians]] organised online performances, often with musical sections referencing the fact of social isolation or home-quarantine, via their own social media platforms. Some were especially planned and prepared; some were impromptu. For example, cellist [[Yo-Yo Ma|YoYo Ma]] performed \"Going Home\" by [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]], the [[West Australian Symphony Orchestra]] renamed themselves the \"West Australian Social Distancing Orchestra\" and played a re-arranged version of ''[[Bol\u00e9ro]]'' by [[Maurice Ravel]] and an amateur choir gathered the contributions of more than 1000 people from 18 countries to create a video performance of \u201cClose To You\u201d by [[The Carpenters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HezxInuN1YA|title=Couch Choir - (They Long To Be) Close To You|last=|first=|date=22 March 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Many musicians, singers and songwriters adapted to the crisis by turning to teaching online as there was both a sudden increase in people wanting to learn instruments, and a drop in paid public performance opportunities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lamond|first=Scott|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-cant-stop-the-music-as-online-lessons-in-demand/12089060|title=Coronavirus sees ARIA-winning musicians turn online teachers as students flock to lessons|date=26 March 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral special remote-participation [[concerts]] were organised to provide entertainment to the public, and to raise awareness methods to combat the virus, notably [[physical distancing]]. The [[iHeart Living Room Concert for America]] concert (hosted by [[Elton John]]) was broadcast on American TV and radio, while ''[[Together at Home]]'' is a \"virtual concert series\". The quickly organised \"Instagram Live Music Festival\"''Isol Aid'' (a reference to [[Live Aid]]) of 72 Australian bands was broadcast on the weekend of 21\u201322 March. Each artist performed from wherever the were [[Isolation (health care)|self isolating]] and \"... play a 20-minute set streamed live on their Instagram accounts, and then tag-team the next artist to play\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/isol-aid-instagram-live-music-festival-coronavirus-covid-19/12072202|title=Isol-Aid is a stacked Aussie livestreaming music festival that's happening this weekend|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-03-19|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://linktr.ee/isolaidfestival|title=@isolaidfestival|website=Linktree|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>.\n\n====[[Performing arts]]====\nNew (or a newly expanded range) free [[online streaming]] of previously recorded theatrical performances was provided by many institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Convery|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/20/livestreaming-schedule-music-art-literature-and-events-from-australia-and-beyond|title=Livestreaming schedule: music, art, literature and events from Australia and beyond|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Rawson|first2=Sharnee|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> For example, the [[Metropolitan Opera]] of New York broadcast a new opera each evening, including an entire [[Ring Cycle]] performed during the 2010\u201312 seasons, via their own app,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/in-wake-of-season-cancellation-metropolitan-opera-continues-free-streaming-series-with-a-week-of-wagner|title=In Wake of Season Cancellation, Metropolitan Opera Continues Free Streaming Series With a Week of Wagner|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Playbill]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] company of Moscow made available six of their recorded performances via [[YouTube]] for 24 hours each.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/03/27/spend-an-evening-at-the-bolshoi-a69775|title=Spend an Evening at the Bolshoi|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=The Moscow Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-russia-bolshoi-idUSKBN21E35D|title=Russia's Bolshoi Theater goes online as coronavirus curbs public life|date=2020-03-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en}}</ref> The [[West End theatre|West End]] production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows (musical)|The Wind in the Willows]]'' was also streamed for UK residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/theatre-and-arts/wind-in-the-willows-streaming-west-end|title=You Can Screen The West End's Wind In The Willows Online For Free|date=2020-03-18|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIndividual actors, such as [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[Sam Neill]], entertained from isolation in order to \"...be in this together and that this has to take the form of being apart\", as Neill described his contribution of [[comedic relief]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Craven|first=Peter|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/movies/when-the-going-got-tough-sam-neill-got-out-his-ukulele-20200330-p54fd8.html|title=When the going got tough, Sam Neill got out his ukulele|date=1 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Stewart, a trained Shakespearian actor, broadcast himself reading one [[Shakespearean sonnet|sonnet]] each day via [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/books-and-poetry/patrick-stewart-is-treating-twitter-to-one-shakespearan-sonnet-a-day-during-lockdown|title=Patrick Stewart Is Treating Twitter To One Shakespeare Sonnet A Day During Lockdown|date=2020-03-25|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n====[[Radio]]====\n[[SiriusXM]] offered free streaming of their subscription-based radio service from April 2 to May 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=SiriusXM Offers Free Streaming Amid Social Distancing |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/siriusxm-offers-free-streaming-amid-social-distancing/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[NPR]] continued to produce new episodes of its ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' quiz [[panel show]], although it was no longer recorded in front of a live audience, and live tapings in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] and [[Atlanta]] were canceled .<ref>{{cite web |last1=News |first1=N. P. R. |title=A message from NPR on programming |url=https://news.wbfo.org/post/message-npr-programming |website=news.wbfo.org |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Taping of NPR's 'Wait, Wait' quiz show at Shea's postponed |url=https://buffalonews.com/2020/03/17/taping-of-npr-wait-wait-quiz-show-at-sheas-postponed/ |website=The Buffalo News |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en-us |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ruggieri |first1=Melissa |title=NPR cancels Thursday live taping of 'Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me' at the Fox Theatre |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/music/npr-cancels-thursday-live-taping-wait-wait-don-tell-the-fox-theatre/wb24HTGK9GaKFgd64XnK2O/ |website=Atlanta Journal-Constitution |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=english}}</ref>\n\n==Impacts==\n===Budgets and employment===\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDue to the closures, revenues for cultural organisations reliant on ticket sales were expected to cause devastating effects upon revenues, with consequent impacts upon organisational staffing, and on independent artists and professionals. This is due to the fact that the arts and culture is a sector of national economies characterised by particularly a high proportion of self-employment.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/arts-council-england-emergency-relief-fund-1814829|title=Arts Council England Has Launched a $190 Million Emergency Relief Package for Creative Organizations and Artists|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> For example, by the 20th of March the [[Cirque du Soleil]] had [[laid off]] 95% of its workforce and closed [[traveling circus]] performances operating in seven countries,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/cirque-de-soleil-canada-coronavirus-staff-fired-1493386|title=Cirque du Soleil lays off 95 percent of its workforce after coronavirus forces closure of all its shows globally|last=Cole|first=Brendan|date=2020-03-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The world commercial art market declined 5% in 2019 compared to the previous year, and is expected to decline further in 2020 \u2013 with 6 of the world's 10 largest auction houses operating exclusively in China. Major art fairs such as [[Hong Kong Arts Festival]] and [[Art Basel]] were cancelled, furthering a shift towards online purchases and the creation of VIP \"online viewing rooms\" rather than physical displaying at [[art auctions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-coronavirus-pandemic-corona-panic-is-shaking-up-worlds-global-art-market-starting-in-hong-kong/a-52651815|title=The coronavirus is shaking up the world's art market in unexpected ways|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|website=DW.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nArts and culture sector budgetary and employment reports from individual countries included:<br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. [[Opera Australia]] \u2013 the nation's largest [[performing arts]] company \u2013 temporarily stood down nearly all its staff<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/exit-stage-left-opera-australia-leads-arts-shutdown-20200325-p54dq1|title=Exit stage left: Opera Australia leads arts shutdown|date=2020-03-26|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> amid speculation it would also need to sell major assets in order to avoid [[bankruptcy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/opera-australia-looks-to-sell-offs-to-stay-afloat-20200316-p54ai2.html|title=Opera Australia looks to sell-offs to stay afloat|last=Galvin|first=Nick|date=2020-03-16|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> By the 23rd of March, 255,000 cultural events had been cancelled with an estimated revenue loss of $A280 million, self reported through the crowdsourced website ILostMyGig.net.au.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-what-the-latest-stimulus-measures-mean-for-australian-artists-and-arts-organisations-134233|title=Coronavirus: what the latest stimulus measures mean for Australian artists and arts organisations|last=Caust|first=Jo|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. In March, when many institutions closed for the first time since [[WWII]], the state-funded museum sector had been valued at \u20ac27 billion or 1.6% of national GDP \u2013 slightly smaller than the agriculture sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/coronavirus-l-impatto-negativo-chiusure-musei-che-valgono-l-16percento-pil-AC4pFCMB|title=Coronavirus, l'impatto negativo delle chiusure sui musei (che valgono l'1,6% del Pil)|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. As the pandemic spread and closures became the standard not the exception, institutions started publishing expected revenue shortfall calculations, began to fire staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AMTransparency/status/1242869675425443840|title=This will be a thread for tracking museum layoff news.|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|publisher=Art + Museum Transparency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> For example: the [[Metropolitan opera]] expects to lose $60m in revenue;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woolfe|first=Zachary|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/arts/music/metropolitan-opera-coronavirus.html|title=Metropolitan Opera Cancels Season Over Virus and Faces $60 Million Loss|date=2020-03-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the [[Metropolitan Museum]] expects to lose $100m in revenue with likely layoffs;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/arts/design/met-museum-coronavirus-closure.html|title=Met Museum Prepares for $100 Million Loss and Closure Till July|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and SFMOMA [[furlough]]ed 300 staff in the expectation of a 40% decrease in revenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13877653/sfmoma-to-lay-off-or-furlough-over-300-museum-staff|title=SFMOMA to Lay Off or Furlough Over 300 Museum Staff|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=2020-03-27|website=[[KQED]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Science Museum of Minnesota]] expected to lose $15m in revenue over three months. Consequently, it \"temporarily\" [[laid off]] most of its staff in an announcement via a [[Google Hangouts]] videocall in late March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-science-museum-children-s-museum-lay-off-most-staff-in-wake-of-covid-19-outbreak/569063662/|title=Science Museum of Minnesota, Children's Museum temporarily lay off most staff in wake of COVID-19|website=Star Tribune|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Meanwhile, staff across the museum began to unionise, even though \"[[Social distancing]] orders prevent the in-person meetings required to sign the cards required to file for union elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tinyletter.com/artandmuseumtransparency/letters/art-museum-transparency-newsletter-2-march-2020|title=Art + Museum Transparency Newsletter #2 -- March 2020|last=|first=|date=2020-03-26|website=artandmuseumtransparency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Financial relief ===\nWith the extensive financial disruption across all areas of the economy, many governments announced [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] and [[Bailout|economic bailout]] packages which included specific resources for the arts and cultural sectors. Equally, various [[charities]] and industry bodies raised funds to support their sector.\n\nArts and culture sector financial stimulus packages from individual countries included:\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. petition of over 50 arts and culture organisations (including peak bodies from the music, dance, visual arts, museums, writers' and indigenous arts groups) requested a financial aid package \"...to a value of 2% of the $111.7 billion [cultural and creative] industry\" and requesting the Prime Minister \"...issue a public statement recognising the value of our industry to all Australians\" and noting that the industry had not yet recovered from the impact of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://visualarts.net.au/news-opinion/2020/creative-industry-unites/|title=Creative industry unites to secure Australia's cultural life|website=NAVA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The library professional association [[Australian Library and Information Association|ALIA]] announced a \"relief fund\" of payments up to $500 to cover the cost of essential expenses for its members \"...experiencing a reduction in income as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alia.org.au/alia-covid-19-relief-fund|title=ALIA COVID-19 Relief Fund|last=|first=|date=2020-04-03|website=www.alia.org.au|publisher=Australian Library and Information Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. The minister for culture [[Franck Riester]] announced that employees of cultural institutions currently receiving unemployment benefits calculated over 12 months will see the confinement period withdrawn from the calculation <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.francemusique.fr/actualite-musicale/coronavirus-le-gouvernement-annonce-des-mesures-pour-les-intermittents-du-spectacle-82453 |title=Coronavirus : le gouvernement annonce des mesures pour les intermittents du spectacle |language=fr|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. The minister for culture [[Monika Gr\u00fctters]] declared that \"artists are not only indispensable, but also vital, especially now.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/german-bailout-50-billion-1815396|title=Germany Has Rolled Out a Staggering \u20ac50 Billion Aid Package For Small Businesses That Boosts Artists and Galleries\u2014and Puts Other Countries to Shame|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The statement was made while announcing a \u20ac50 billion stimulus package for small business and freelancers \u2013 explicitly including the creative sectors.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. The Swedish Minister of Culture [[Amanda Lind]] presented a 1 billion [[Swedish krona|SEK]] support package for sports and culture, where 500 million SEK was earmarked for culture (not including government agencies like the [[Royal Dramatic Theatre]] and [[Kungliga Operan]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=En miljard i akut st\u00f6d till kultur och idrott|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/coronaviruset/en-miljard-i-akut-stod-till-kultur-och-idrott/|publisher=Expressen|access-date=2020-03-25|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. [[The Film and TV Charity]] created an emergency relief fund in order to \"provide emergency short-term relief to active workers and freelancers who have been directly affected by the closure of productions across the UK\", with an initial donation of \u00a31m from [[Netflix]] and by \u00a3500,000 from the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bfi-uk-film-and-tv-charity-set-up-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-with-1m-donation-from-netflix-1202890966/|title=BFI & UK Film And TV Charity Set Up Covid-19 Emergency Relief Fund With \u00a31M Donation From Netflix|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=2020-03-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bbc-donates-to-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-1202894127/|title=BBC Joins Netflix In Making $600,000 Donation To Coronavirus Emergency Relief Fund|last=Kanter|first=Jake|date=2020-03-27|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Museums Association]] called upon the UK government to divert \u00a3120m that was intended for the [[Festival of Britain|Festival of Britain 2022]] to bail out museums in financial distress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/17032020-museum-closures-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Museums and galleries close as coronavirus emergency intensifies|last=Kendall Adams|first=Geraldine|date=17 March 2020|website=Museums Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> [[Arts Council England]] announced \u00a3160 million would be made available for arts organisations, including \u00a350 million for organisations it does not usually fund and \u00a320 million for individual and freelance artists.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Paul Hamlyn Foundation]] announced that the usual competitive selection process for their \"Award for Artists\" program would be removed, and that instead of ten awards of \u00a360,000, each of the more than 100 previously nominated eligible applicants would automatically receive \u00a310,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phf.org.uk/news/1-million-awarded-to-visual-artists-and-composers-in-the-uk/|title=\u00a31 million awarded to visual artists and composers in the UK|date=2020-04-06|website=Paul Hamlyn Foundation|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A petition was begun by the [[American Alliance of Museums]] to request that the museum sector was included in any future [[economic stimulus]] from the United States government,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congressweb.com/AAM/67|title=Tell Congress: Include Museums in COVID-19 Economic Relief|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> while the Metropolitan museum was more specific \u2013 requesting $4 billion for at-risk museums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/metropolitan-museum-of-art-congress-1813665|title=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Is Calling on the US Government to Bail Out At-Risk Museums With $4 Billion in Aid|date=2020-03-24|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn late March the United States federal government announced a $2 trillion economic stimulus package. It included: \"$75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] and $75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], which can pass on the money to institutions that need it. Another $50 million was designated to the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]], which distributes funds to museums and libraries.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/arts/coronavirus-arts-bailout.html|title=Arts Groups, Facing Their Own Virus Crisis, Get a Piece of the Stimulus|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> While a common argument in the USA against the cultural sector receiving stimulus funding was that \"Arts groups may be 'nice,' but they\u2019re far from 'necessary.'\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Copyright ===\nAcademic librarians in the United States made public statements on the applicability and importance of the role of the [[fair use]] copyright exception for \"Emergency Remote Teaching & Research\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/10baTITJbFRh7D6dHVVvfgiGP2zqaMvm0EHHZYf2cBRk/mobilebasic?urp=gmail_link|title=Public Statement: Fair Use & Emergency Remote Teaching & Research|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Cornell University Library]] made the advice explicit, noting in a new official library policy recommending, \"...that faculty may scan course material in amounts that may exceed customary fair use limits under normal circumstances. Fair use provides flexibility to permit faculty scan broader amounts of course material than normal during these exigent circumstances.\" and noted that library staff were no longer allowed to work on-site and therefore not able to scan materials on behalf of teaching staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://copyright.cornell.edu/covid|title=COVID-19 & Copyright at Cornell {{!}} Copyright Information Center|website=copyright.cornell.edu|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> [[File:National_Emergency_Library.png|thumb|right|the \"National Emergency Library\" of the Internet Archive on 24 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/nationalemergencylibrary|title=National Emergency Library : Free Texts : Free Download, Borrow and Streaming : Internet Archive|last=|first=|date=|website=archive.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>]]\nThe ''National Emergency Library'' of the Internet Archive \u2013 which suspended waitlists for access to digitised in-copyright books citing the justification of Fair Use during the pandemic \u2013 was criticised as \"piracy masquerading as public service\" and copyright infringement, especially by the [[Association of American Publishers]] and [[Authors Guild]]<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/books/internet-archive-emergency-library.html|title='Emergency' Online Library Draws Ire of Some Authors|date=2020-03-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> as well as drawing public critique from several noted authors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/internet-archive-national-emergency-library-controversy.html|title=The Internet Archive Started an \"Emergency\" Online Library. Authors Are Furious.|last=Hampton|first=Rachelle|date=2020-04-01|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The Internet Archive defended its program by emphasising that: the collection consisted primarily of older in-copyright works without digital surrogates; it is a temporary program; authors can chose to opt-out; and the works are chosen for the educational not commercial value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.archive.org/2020/03/30/internet-archive-responds-why-we-released-the-national-emergency-library/|title=Internet Archive responds: Why we released the National Emergency Library {{!}} Internet Archive Blogs|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/controversy-surrounds-national-emergency-library-180974554/|title=Why the National Emergency Library Is So Controversial|last=Machemer|first=Theresa|website=Smithsonian Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nThe libraries of universities and of the [[National Research Council (Italy)|National Research Council]] in Italy petitioned [[academic publishers]] to provide temporary [[open access]] to publications in order to medical staff, scientific researchers, and the general public access during the national emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centumcellae.it/cronaca/appello-per-il-diritto-di-accesso-alla-conoscenza-scientifica-in-stato-di-emergenza/|title=APPELLO PER IL DIRITTO DI ACCESSO ALLA CONOSCENZA SCIENTIFICA IN STATO DI EMERGENZA|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=Centumcellae|language=it-IT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n[[LeVar Burton]], host of ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'', announced his desire to perform live-streamed readings of books for his podcast ''LeVar Reads'' but that copyright law was unclear as to whether this was allowed. [[Neil Gaiman]] replied to Burton via Twitter, giving him permission to read any of his works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/939vjv/please-dont-sue-levar-burton-for-reading-soothing-stories-to-scared-children|title=Please Don't Sue LeVar Burton for Reading Soothing Stories to Scared Children|last=Cole|first=Samantha|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious online training workshops were organised for cultural heritage to learn about relevant risks and [[Copyright exceptions|exceptions to copyright]] when providing online services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/open-glam/copyright-open-access-for-glams-in-the-age-of-covid-3a35e67f7a1|title=Copyright & Open Access for GLAMs in the age of COVID-19|last=|first=|date=2020-03-24|website=Medium|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Equally, [[digital strategy]] workshops<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usingdata.com/usingdata/2020/3/19/free-strategy-workshops-march-23-april-3|title=Free strategy workshops March 23 \u2013 April 3|website=Usingdata|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and live Q&A sessions with experts were organised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AAMers/status/1242798776655413249|title=What #COVID19 questions do you want to pose to the museum field? Comment below or DM us to include it in our #MuseumsDiscussCOVID19 Tweet chat! TODAY 3-4 pm|publisher=American Alliance of Museums|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n=== New cultural works ===\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nWith thorough and global disruption society to an unprecedented level, there is the expectation of many and diverse cultural works created which reference or are inspired by the pandemic and its effects. One gallery director said: \"There will definitely be an explosion in new material.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dye|first=Josh|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/perplexing-and-confusing-art-gallery-of-nsw-director-grapples-with-coronavirus-crisis-20200327-p54emd.html|title='Perplexing and confusing': Art Gallery of NSW director grapples with coronavirus crisis|date=28 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{CC-notice|cc=by4|url=https://www.ifla.org/covid-19-and-libraries|author(s)=[[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions|IFLA]]}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage}}\n[[Category:2020 in arts]]\n[[Category:Cultural heritage]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|arts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{current related||2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Globalize|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:Closed library - Island Bay.jpg|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Announcement posted in the door of a [[public library]] in [[Island Bay, New Zealand]] that it is closed due to the pandemic, and will waive all [[Late fees|late return fees]].]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] had a sudden and substantial impact on the [[performing arts]] and cultural heritage ([[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAM]]) sectors. The global health crisis and the uncertainly resulting from it profoundly affected organisations' operations as well as individuals \u2013 both employed and independent \u2013 across the sector. Arts and culture sector organisations attempted to uphold their (often publicly funded) mission to provide access to cultural heritage to the community; maintain the safety of their employees, collections, and the public; while reacting to the unexpected change in their [[business model]] with an unknown end.\n\nBy March 2020, across the world most cultural institutions had been indefinitely closed (or at least with their services radically curtailed) exhibitions, events and performances cancelled or postponed. In response there were intensive efforts to provide alternative services through digital platforms, to maintain essential activities with minimal revenue, and simultaneously an awareness that there would be many new [[creative works]] which had been inspired by the event.\n\nMany individuals across the sector would temporarily or permanently lose contracts or employment with varying degrees of warning and financial assistance available. Equally, [[financial stimulus]] from governments and charities for artists, would provide greatly differing levels of support depending on the sector and the country. The public demand for cultural activities was expected to return, but in at an unknown time and with the assumption that different kinds of experiences would be popular.\n\n==Closures== \nThrough the first months of 2020, arts and culture sector organisations around the world progressively restricted their public activities and closed completely due to the coronavirus pandemic. Starting with China, and East Asia, by mid-to-late March most organisations worldwide had either closed voluntarily or by government mandate. This included libraries,<ref name=\"IFLA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ifla.org/covid-19-and-libraries|title=COVID-19 and the Global Library Field|publisher=[[IFLA]]|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> museums,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/coronavirus-museum-closures-worldwide-1202680933/|title=See a List of Coronavirus-Related Closures at Museums Around the World|last=Solomon|first=Claire Selvin,Tessa|last2=Selvin|first2=Claire|date=2020-03-12|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26|last3=Solomon|first3=Tessa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LNCETkPjgcNdmybrwE5g2JEK4KpIfhKThnws1QqgjqE/mobilebasic|title=Museum Responses - COVID-19|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> theatre and stage productions,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2020/mar/13/coronavirus-culture-arts-films-gigs-festivals-cancellations|title=Coronavirus and culture \u2013 a list of major cancellations|date=2020-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and arts festivals.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2020, dates for re-opening and expectations for when cultural organisation can fully \"return to normal\" are unknown for most of the world. Survey data from March in the USA indicated that, when museums were permitted to reopen, the public \"intent to visit\" metric for cultural activities should be unchanged overall from prior to the pandemic \u2013 but with a shifted preference for the ''kind'' of activity. Data indicated there would be a decreased willingness for attendance of activities in confined spaces, large immobile groups (such as cinemas), or tactile activities; with an increase in interest for activities outdoors or with large spaces (such as zoos and botanic gardens).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/25/how-is-covid-19-impacting-likelihood-to-attend-different-cultural-entities-data/|title=Post-Pandemic, Which Cultural Entity Types Are People More Likely to Revisit? (DATA)|date=2020-03-25|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/23/weekly-data-update-how-covid-19-is-impacting-intentions-to-visit-cultural-entities-march-23-2020/|title=DATA UPDATE: How COVID-19 is Impacting Intentions to Visit Cultural Entities - March 23, 2020|date=2020-03-23|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The most commonly cited reasons for the public to \"feel safe\" in returning would be: the availability of a [[COVID-19 vaccine|vaccine]], governments lifting travel restrictions, knowing that other people had visited, whether the activity/institution was outdoors, and the provision of [[hand sanitiser]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/04/01/what-will-make-people-feel-safe-attending-a-cultural-entity-again-data/|title=What Will Make People Feel Safe Attending a Cultural Entity Again? (DATA)|date=2020-04-01|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nBy early April at least one museum had announced its permanent closure, with more expected to follow.\n\n''The following is a list of notable closures, announcements and policies affecting the cultural sector.<br>For comprehensive lists:''\n{{See also|List of public venues and institutions closed during the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}} \n{{See also|List of events affected by the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n'''Africa'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Egypt}}. From March 23 until March 31, 2020 all museums and archaeological sites in Egypt were closed to the public for sterilization and disinfection. During this period a programme to raise the awareness of the sites and museums\u2019 employees on ways of prevention and protection against the virus took place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cairoscene.com/Buzz/Egypt-to-Close-All-Museums-and-Archaeological-Sites|title= Egypt to close all museums and archaeological sites}}</ref>\n\n'''Asia'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flagicon|China}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]]. On 23 January 2020 all museums were closed throughout mainland China, As the first country for the virus to spread, China was also the first to close its GLAMs.<ref name=\":0\" /> By Mid-March Chinese institutions had slowly and cautiously begun to allow various public activities to be restored with the [[Shanghai Museum]] and the [[Power Station of Art]] (also in Shanghai) reopening on the 13th. Both had restricted visitor numbers and the latter noted that, \u201cWe have also prepared a temporary quarantine area on every floor in case of any emergencies. All visitors must have their temperature taken, as well as present their ID card and registered health code, before entering.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/china-japan-south-korea-museums-reopen-coronavirus-1202680994/|title=Museums in China, South Korea, Japan Begin to Reopen After Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Solomon|first=Tessa|last2=Solomon|first2=Tessa|date=2020-03-13|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Some other private galleries in China had begun to open, as had some institutions in South Korea and Japan with limited service (such as by private tour only). By the end of the month 40% of mainland China's tourism attractions had reopened yet most art venues remained closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/china-south-korea-and-japan-start-to-reopen-museums|title=China, South Korea and Japan start to reopen museums after strict coronavirus lockdown|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Hong Kong}}. Following the mainland, Hong Kong closed its museums five days later.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Japan}}. On 28 February Japan announced all museums would be closed \"until 17 March\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in|Qatar}}. Qatar museums run by the state closed on 12 March. A forthcoming collaborative show on Picasso's Studio's due to be held by the [[Fire Station (gallery)|Fire Station]] and [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso]] has been indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |South Korea}}. On 23 February, one month after mainland China, South Korea closed all museums \"until further notice\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Europe'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts -->\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Austria}}. All federal public museums were closed by directors in response to government precautionary measures banning large events and arrivals from Italy. The [[Albertina Modern]] museum was supposed to open on 13 March but this opening was indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Belgium}}. All cultural activities regardless of size were banned by the government from 14 March, which involved the closure of the [[Jan van Eyck]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Ghent]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. Weeks earlier than French government regulations required it, staff of [[The Louvre]] \"almost unanimously\" voted to force the closure of the museum on the 1st of March, due to concerns for their own health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51697644|title=Staff force Louvre closure over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> It closed for three days, reopened,<ref>{{cite web|title=Coronavirus: Louvre museum in Paris reopens after staff walkout|url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20200301/frances-louvre-museum-closed-due-to-virus-fears|website=www.thelocal.fr|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> accepted only visitors with pre-booked tickets from the 9th,<ref name=\":0\" /> then closed definitively on the 13th by government mandate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200313-france-s-louvre-museum-and-versailles-palace-to-shut-over-coronavirus-crisis|title=Louvre, Versailles and Eiffel Tower close over coronavirus crisis|date=2020-03-13|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Reconstruction of the [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame cathedral]] following [[Notre-Dame de Paris fire|the 2019 fire]] was also halted because of worker security.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. On 16 March 2020, the German chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] announced in a press conference that the government and [[minister-president]]s had together agreed upon guidelines to limit social contacts in public spaces. Theatres, opera houses, concert halls, museums, exhibition spaces, cinemas, amusement parks and zoos needed to close.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/leitlinien-bund-laender-1731000|title=Leitlinien gegen Ausbreitung des Coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|website=Die Bundesregierung|language=de|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. As the worst hit country in Europe during February and March, national closures were announced on the 23rd of February with an initial reopening date of 1 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/la-cultura-chiusa-tempi-coronavirus-ACNKCpLB|title=La cultura chiusa ai tempi del coronavirus|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Museums outside the \"red zone\" of highly infected areas in the North were then permitted to re-open as long as visitors stayed 1 meter apart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/italian-museums-reopen-following-government-green-light|title=Coronavirus: Louvre closes while Italian museums reopen following government green light|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> this was later rescinded and all institution were closed until at least 3 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/rome-s-blockbuster-raphael-exhibition-closes|title=Coronavirus in Italy: Ai Weiwei criticised for 'insensitive' pasta meme and Raphael blockbuster closes|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The closure forced the indefinite postponement of the forthcoming \u201cmega-exhibition\u201d of [[Raphael]] to be held at the [[Scuderie del Quirinale]] in Rome. Originally timed to coincide with the 500th anniversary of the [[Renaissance art|Renaissance painter's]] death, it was to be the largest number of Raphaels ever displayed together.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Vatican City}}. The [[Vatican Museums]] closed in accordance with the policies of Italy.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Netherlands}}. On 12 March, Amsterdam's [[Rijksmuseum]] and [[Van Gogh Museum]] announced they would close until at least the end of that month.<ref name=\":0\" /> The following day, having previously announced the reading room and exhibition would remain open, the [[Nationaal Archief|National Archives]] announced their complete closure until April 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaalarchief.nl/beleven/nieuws/studiezaal-en-tentoonstelling-nationaal-archief-tijdelijk-gesloten|title=Studiezaal en tentoonstelling Nationaal Archief tijdelijk gesloten|website=Nationaal Archief|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>  On 30 March, the painting ''[[The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen]]'' (1884) by [[Vincent van Gogh]] was stolen from the [[Singer Laren|Singer Laren museum]] while the museum was closed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/i-m-absolutely-livid-van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-museum-during-pandemic-20200331-p54fgd.html|title='I'm absolutely livid': Van Gogh painting stolen from museum during pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Poland}}. On 11 March a regional government \"recommendation\" was made that all cultural venues in the [[Tricity, Poland|tricity]] area be closed for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kultura.trojmiasto.pl/Teatry-odwolane-imprezy-spektakle-koronawirus-w-Trojmiescie-n143084.html|title=Teatry zamkni\u0119te przynajmniej na 2 tygodnie|date=2020-03-10|website=trojmiasto.pl|language=pl|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Museums, including the [[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]], and other cultural venues such as theatres and cinemas were then closed by the national government with an initial re-opening date of 25 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Russia}}. The [[Garage Museum of Contemporary Art]] was one of the first to announce its closure from 14 March. Many [[Moscow]] museums announced closures in response to the mayor's ban on gatherings of 50 people or more on 17 March, and late that day the Russian culture ministry ordered the suspension of all public activities by federal and regional institutions, which resulted in many more closures from 18 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Spain}}. On 11 March, publicly owned museums in Madrid, including [[The Prado]], were closed indefinitely.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Sagrada Fam\u00edlia]] indefinitely suspended construction works and closed the monument to visitors on 13 March and the [[Guggenheim Museum Bilbao]] closed on 14 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. On 18 March, the Swedish network and cooperation organisation for public museums of national interest, ''Centralmuseernas samarbetsr\u00e5d'', recommended all their 13 members to close their public venues if the risk for transmission of the virus was assessed as high in their respective regions. Only two of them stayed open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigesmuseer.se/nyheter/2020/03/cms-rekommenderar-stangning-av-centralmuseer-i-omraden-med-hog-smittspridning/|title=CMS rekommenderar st\u00e4ngning av centralmuseer i omr\u00e5den med h\u00f6g smittspridning|date=2020-03-18|website=Sveriges museer|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. The earliest closures of cultural institutions in the UK were announced from 13 March by [[Wellcome Collection]], [[South London Gallery]], the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]], [[The Photographers' Gallery]] and [[Amgueddfa Cymru \u2013 National Museum Wales|Amgueddfa Cymru]].<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|last=McGivern|first=Hannah|last2=Kenney|first2=Nancy|date=14 March 2020|website=The Art Newspaper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Many other organisations announced closures on the 17 and 18 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/london-museums-galleries-exhibitions-closed-coronavirus-a4389351.html|title=The London galleries and museums that are closed due to coronavirus|last=Paskett|first=Zoe|date=17 March 2020|website=Evening Standard|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51928526|title=Tate, V&A and Natural History Museum to close|date=2020-03-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] closed all ticketed properties by 20 March but aimed to keep gardens and parklands open, free of charge so that people could access the open space whilst social distancing.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe planned major exhibition at the [[National Gallery]] in London of [[Artemisia Gentileschi]], set to open on April 4, was postponed for an indeterminate time due not only to the gallery's closure but also the inability of artworks on loan from Italy and America being unable to fly during the global shutdown in air traffic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jones|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/16/artemisia-gentileschi-national-gallery-exhibition-postponed-coronavirus|title=With coronavirus, the curse of Artemisia Gentileschi strikes again|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The [[Glasgow International]] 2020 arts festival was posponed until 2021.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n'''North America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A \"flurry\" of museums in New York, Boston and Washington all announced their closure on March 12, led by the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and coinciding with the New York Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] declaring a city wide emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/metropolitan-museum-of-art-to-shut-down-because-of-coronavirus|title=Led by Metropolitan Museum of Art, a flurry of US museums say they are shutting down because of coronavirus|last=Kenny|first=Nancy|date=2020-03-12|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[The Broadway League]] announced on the same day that all [[Broadway theatres]] would cease performances for at least a month, even though New York State governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] had at the time allowed them to continue at 50% capacity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/health/broadway-coronavirus-update/index.html|title=Broadway theaters to suspend all performances because of coronavirus|author1=Taylor Romine |author2=Eric Levenson |author3=Javi Morgado|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On March 17, two days before the [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|first State to declare a \"stay at home\" order]], the [[American Library Association]] \"strongly recommended\" that all academic, public, and school libraries close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/news/press-releases/2020/03/ala-executive-board-recommends-closing-libraries-public|title=ALA Executive Board recommends closing libraries to public|last=|first=|date=2020-03-17|website=|publisher=[[American Library Association]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n'''Oceania'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. Beginning from the second week of March Australian institutions began announcing reduced services, and then complete closures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wragge.github.io/closed-glams-covid19/|title=Australian GLAMs and COVID-19|website=closed-glams-covid19|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Opera Australia]] announced it would close on the 15th.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://operawire.com/opera-australia-cancels-performances-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Opera Australia Cancels Performances Due to Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|website=Opera Wire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On the 24th the national closure of all cultural institutions was required.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |New Zealand}}. New Zealand implemented a policy on March 23 that all institutions would be closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndf.org.nz/covid19-and-nz-glams|title=COVID-19 and NZ GLAMs|website=National Digital Forum|language=en-NZ|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]] closed from 6pm March 20.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Campbell|first=Georgina|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318548|title=Coronavirus: Te Papa museum to close for two weeks|date=20 March 2020|work=New Zealand Herald|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Auckland War Memorial Museum]] announced that it would close from March 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/service-pages/alerts/covid-19?utm_source=wordfly&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=TemporaryMuseumClosure&utm_content=version_A|title=Auckland Museum is temporarily closed}}</ref>\n\n'''South America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Argentina}}. All the museums, cultural activities and gatherings were cancelled in the city of Buenos Aires on the 12th of March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/cultura/coronavirus-argentina-disponen-cierre-temporario-museos-ciudad_0_Hgfv9C32.html|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: disponen el cierre temporario de todos los museos de la Ciudad|last=|website=www.clarin.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> National libraries continue to offer means of contact through the main educational website of the Ministry of Education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.educ.ar/recursos/151053/bibliotecas-en-casa-en-seguimos-conectados?from=150858&fbclid=IwAR3S3KjeZavdRV6gjOCfJxVUz6Xu5L0Eqfep7SBTT5l1RrOOKvuHQDML0tY|title=#BibliotecasEnCasa en Seguimos Educando - Educ.ar|website=www.educ.ar|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Brazil}}. Museums which have closed{{when|date=March 2020}} in Brazil include the Museum of Art of S\u00e3o Paulo Assis Chateaubriand, the Pinacoteca, the Ita\u00fa Cultural, the Museum of Contemporary Art of the University of S\u00e3o Paulo, the Institute Tomie Ohtake, the Institute Moreira Salles, and the Museum of Tomorrow in Rio de Janeiro and the Instituto Inhotim contemporary art centre in Brumadinho.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Permanent closure ===\n{{Incomplete list|date=April 2020}}\nThe first cultural institution to announced its permanent closure as a result of the pandemic was [[Indianapolis Contemporary]], a contemporary art museum founded in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/arts/2020/04/03/indianapolis-contemporary-art-museum-shuts-down-coronavirus/5115668002/|title=Indianapolis Contemporary art museum shuts down, citing economic damage from coronavirus|last=Bongiovanni|first=Domenica|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> An announcement from its board on April 3, 2020 stated that \"We have concluded our operations are not sustainable. We are not alone as other arts institutions struggle in this crisis.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indcontemporary.org/press-release/ic-to-close|title=I/C Board Announces Plans To Close|website=Indianapolis Contemporary|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nFacing at least several weeks of closure of their buildings and publicly-accessible spaces, many cultural sector organisations and individual artists turned to digital activities as a way to continue fulfilling their organisational mission and obtain or retain an audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@kajsahartig/museums-delivering-value-online-some-thoughts-during-the-covid-19-crisis-193fc0a58d22|title=Museums delivering value online \u2014 some thoughts during the Covid-19 crisis|last=Hartig|first=Kajsa|date=2020-03-29|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Farago|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/arts/design/coronavirus-digital-artists.html|title=The Merry-Go-Round Stopped. What Sort of Art Will Emerge?|date=2020-03-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For example, the [[BBC]] launched a \"virtual festival of the arts\" called ''Culture in quarantine''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/culture-in-quarantine|title=BBC - BBC Arts announces new programmes for Culture In Quarantine - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Sydney Biennale]] became the first international [[arts festival]] to go entirely digital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/the-biennale-of-sydney-is-moving-online-1811871|title=Dawn of the Online Biennial Era? The Biennale of Sydney Becomes the First Major International Art Show to Go Virtual|last=Rea|first=Naomi|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Artnet]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\nHaving been the first country to enforce quarantine upon its population, museums in China were also the first to provide new digital services (primarily for a domestic audience, but to a lesser extent also internationally). In January the [[National Cultural Heritage Administration]] (NCHA) said they would \"encourage cultural heritage museums and institutions around the country to utilise existing digital resources and launch online exhibitions as appropriate, providing the public with safe and convenient online services.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/chinas-museums-offer-online-exhibitions-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ar-BBZEOr6|title=China's museums offer online exhibitions amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncha.gov.cn/art/2020/1/28/art_722_158541.html|title=\u5173\u4e8e\u5411\"\u535a\u7269\u9986\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5e73\u53f0\"\u63d0\u4f9b\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5185\u5bb9\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u5021\u8bae\u4e66|website=www.ncha.gov.cn|publisher=[[National Cultural Heritage Administration]]|language=zh|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMany institutions turned to their existing [[social media]] presences to engage their audience online. Quickly, the [[Twitter|Twitter hashtag]] #MuseumFromHome became particularly popular for museums sharing their content in innovative ways. Various institutions were singled out for particular praise by industry analysts for their successful social media content strategy during the shutdown. These included the [[Shedd Aquarium]] in Chicago for filming their penguins visiting other animals; the [[Royal Academy]] in London for asking its followers to draw their own artworks; and the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in Oklahoma for providing an authentic and unusual 'voice' to their social media - from their security guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/museum-social-media-entertains-during-the-covid-19-crisis/|title=Museum Social Media Entertains During the COVID-19 Crisis|date=2020-03-19|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boredpanda.com/national-cowboy-museum-head-of-security-twitter/|title=Cowboy Museum Puts Their Head Of Security In Charge Of Their Twitter, And His Tweets Are Hilariously Wholesome|website=Bored Panda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Individual actors and musicians offered [[impromptu]] performances via their personal accounts from their homes \u2013 singing [[Cover version|covers]], performing live book or [[poetry readings]], or creatively live-streaming themselves doing both normal and unusual activities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stubbins|first=Sinead|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-cabin-fever-the-best-celebrities-to-follow-from-robbie-williams-to-florence-pugh|title=Coronavirus cabin fever: the best celebrities to follow, from Robbie Williams to Florence Pugh|date=2020-03-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nVarious [[internet journalism]] and [[Industry association]]s published lists of new digitally-accessible arts and culture content for their country. Including Argentina,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buenosaires.gob.ar/culturaencasa|title=Cultura en casa|website=Buenos Aires Ciudad - Gobierno de la Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ozglam.info/s/updates/page/welcome|title=Australian GLAM updates|website=ozglam.info|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irishmuseums.org/text-pages/irishmuseumsonline-content-and-resources|title=#IrishMuseumsOnline: content and resources|website=Irish Museums Association|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalist.it/arti/2020/03/13/musei-chiusi-per-coronavirus-cosa-offrono-sul-web-e-social-mentre-iorestoacasa-2054444.html|title=Musei chiusi per Coronavirus: cosa offrono sul web e social mentre #iorestoacasa|website=Globalist|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2020/03/18/coronavirus-dal-louvre-agli-uffizi-i-musei-chiusi-ora-si-visitano-online-cineteche-teatri-e-biblioteche-cosi-la-cultura-arriva-direttamente-a-casa/5739782/|title=Coronavirus, dal Louvre agli Uffizi, i musei chiusi ora si visitano online. Cinema, teatri e biblioteche: cos\u00ec la cultura arriva direttamente a casa|date=2020-03-18|website=Il Fatto Quotidiano|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/19032020-how-digital-platforms-be-used-to-support-musems-during-covid-19-crisis|title=How can digital platforms help museums connect to audiences during Covid-19 emergency|publisher=[[Museums Association]]|website=www.museumsassociation.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kidsinmuseums.org.uk/2020/03/10-museum-activities-to-keep-children-entertained/|title=10 museum activities to keep children entertained|date=2020-03-23|website=Kids in Museums|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===By sector===\n====[[Public aquarium|Aquaria]] and [[zoo]]s====\nThe impact of the pandemic has been a uniquely serious crisis for some zoos \u2013 with reduced revenues for the operators but also reduced opportunities for [[stimulation]] for \"...the most intelligent and social animals \u2013 including [[gorillas]], [[kea]], [[otters]] and [[meerkats]]\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=Roy|first=Eleanor Ainge|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/02/new-zealand-zoos-strive-to-entertain-lonely-inhabitants-amid-lockdown|title=Animal tragic: New Zealand zoos strive to entertain lonely inhabitants amid lockdown|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In order to maintain physical distancing but also still care for the animals, some zookeepers (classed as \"[[Essential worker|essential workers]]\") began living on-site at certain zoos.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mohdin|first=Aamna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/30/the-animals-arent-pleased-how-shut-uk-zoos-are-coping-under-coronavirus-lockdown|title='The animals aren't pleased': UK zoos under coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-03-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Animals who would normally have a regular scheduled public feeding, petting, or performance for zoo visitors were reported to be still \"keeping their appointments\" and noticing that \"omething odd is upI\".<ref name=\":6\" /> n response to the absence of visitors, several institutions launched new [[webcams]] and [[livestreams]] of their animal habitats as well as feeding sessions. In one case, penguins were taken by their [[zookeeper|keepers]] to other animal enclosures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Padilla|first=Mariel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/us/coronavirus-zoos-webcams.html|title=Stuck at Home, You Can Still Explore the Zoo or Aquarium. Some Penguins Could, Too.|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Vigdor|first2=Neil|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/travel/story/2020-03-20/virtual-touring|title=Watching animals helps. A lot. Here are the best webcams|date=2020-03-20|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nDue to the sudden collapse in international travel, the [[wildlife tourism]] sector risks the potential starvation of the animals. Due to the lack of tourists paying for food more than 1,000 [[Elephants in Thailand]] risk starvation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hatton|first=Celia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52110551|title=Thai elephants face starvation as tourism plummets|date=2020-03-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Paddock|first=Richard C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/coronavirus-thailand-elephants.html|title=As Tourism Plummets in Thailand, Elephants Are Out of Work, Too|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-06|last2=Suhartono|first2=Muktita|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Dean|first3=Adam}}</ref> A \"brawl\" of hundreds of [[Long-tailed macaque]] broke out in the streets of [[Lopburi]], Thailand (known as \"monkey city\"), as the animals \u2013 normally sustained by scraps by tourists \u2013 fought for food.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ratcliffe|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/13/fighting-monkeys-highlight-effect-of-coronavirus-on-thailand-tourism|title=Mass monkey brawl highlights coronavirus effect on Thailand tourism|date=2020-03-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In countries wildlife tourism represents a significant portion of employment (such as Tanzania and Namibia), there is concern that a loss of jobs related to conservation will see a rise in [[poaching]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-lockdown-conservation/|title=The Coronavirus Lockdown Is a Threat for Many Animals, Not a Blessing|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\nNadia, a tiger at the [[Bronx Zoo]] in New York, tested positive for COVID-19 in the first week of April after developing a \"dry cough\" after having been infected via an asymptomatic zookeeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/us/tiger-coronavirus-new-york-trnd/index.html|title=A tiger at the Bronx Zoo tests positive for coronavirus|first=Alaa |last=Elassar|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> This was the first known case of a wild animal having been infected via a human (two domestic dogs and a cat had previously been diagnosed).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/04/tiger-coronavirus-covid19-positive-test-bronx-zoo/|title=Tiger tests positive for coronavirus at Bronx Zoo, first known case in the world|date=2020-04-05|website=Animals|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n====[[Film industry|Cinema]] and [[Television industry|television]]====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|l1=Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television|l2=on television}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n\nThe production and release schedule of many films was suspended or delayed, with some awards ceremonies and festivals being cancelled entirely. March 2020 estimates were of approximately $5b losses for the industry.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shoard|first=Catherine|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/cinema-coronavirus-projected-5bn-loss|title=Cinema bullish in the face of coronavirus despite projected $5bn loss|date=2020-03-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Examples of adaptations included the early [[Home video|home media]] release ([[Frozen II|''Frozen II'']]), [[Theatrical release|theatrical releases]] being cancelled entirely (''[[Lost in Russia]]''), and online premieres ([[Enter the Fat Dragon (2020 film)|''Enter the Fat Dragon'']]). \n\nSimilarly, the [[television industry]] saw production halted on many [[Scripted television|scripted]] and [[unscripted television|unscripted]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} shows. This included series which had been running uninterrupted for the proceeding several decades, including: [[The Bold and the Beautiful]] (season 34), [[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]] (season 34), [[Days of Our Lives]] (season 55), [[Home and Away]] (season 33), [[Saturday Night Live]] (season 45), and [[The Young and the Restless]] (season 47). Some shows continue with production but without their normal [[studio audience]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-tv-shows-production-delayed-1202881997/|title=Coronavirus: TV Shows That Have Halted Or Delayed Production Amid Outbreak|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|last2=Pedersen|first2=Erik|date=2020-03-16|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In parallel to the suspension of entertainment content production, there was a marked increase in the use of [[video streaming]] services for entertainment (as well as [[videoconferencing]] services such as [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] for work and education) due to the massive increase of people staying at home \u2013 causing unprecedented strain on global [[internet infrastructure]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-can-the-internet-handle-unprecedented-surge-in-traffic.html|title=The internet is under huge strain because of the coronavirus. Experts say it can cope \u2014 for now|last=Browne|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-27|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In response, [[Netflix]] and [[YouTube]] both decreased the default video quality to [[standard definition]], [[Disney+]] delayed its launch in France, and [[Xbox]] requested developers to schedule software updates at times of lower network congestion.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kang|first=Cecilia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/business/coronavirus-internet-traffic-speed.html|title=Surging Traffic Is Slowing Down Our Internet|date=2020-03-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|last2=Alba|first2=Davey|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Satariano|first3=Adam}}</ref>\n\nDue to the global cancellation of [[professional sports]], the loss of advertising revenue and broadcast rights derived from the [[broadcasting of sports events]] is expected to threaten the financial viability of many competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/20/sports-broadcast-impact-coronavirus/|title=For the sports-entertainment business, coronavirus is taking a huge toll|last=Zeitchik|first=Steven|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n====[[Libraries]]====\nLibraries faced different situations, from maintaining a full service with some restrictions, through providing minimal services, to complete closure. Following publications from in [[The New England Journal of Medicine]], and the [[Journal of Hospital Infection]], the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]] in the United States suggesting that the risk of coronavirus transmission from paper was low. In the light of this, the [[International Federation of Library Associations]] noted that some libraries had imposed a wait period before handling returned books, while others have made it clear that no-one is expected to return borrowed books until things return to normal.<ref name=\"IFLA\" /> Some libraries  stopped programmes which would see people spend longer periods together. Others closed public reading rooms or only allow people to collect books on appointment, either inside or outside of the building \u2013 for example setting up tables, with a [[drive-through]], or book delivery service to especially vulnerable community groups.<ref name=\"IFLA\" />\n\nLibraries of different sizes and purposes around the world worked to provide access to collections and services remotely. For example, the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]] organised [[virtual exhibition]]s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fantasy.bnf.fr/fr|title=Fantasy, retour aux sources|website=Fantasy, retour aux sources|language=fr|publisher=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> the Granby library in [[Quebec City|Quebec]] highlighted content focused on learning new skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lavoixdelest.ca/actualites/covid-19/a-un-clic-de-1300-cours-en-ligne-23003711130c1556504efdc64b1422d2|title=\u00c0 un clic de 1300 cours en ligne|date=2020-03-28|website=La Voix de l\u2019Est|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> and the [[National library of Israel]] announced it would provide free audiobooks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/national-library-offers-free-audiobooks-amid-coronavirus-closures-621664|title=National Library offers free audiobooks amid coronavirus closures|website=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Many [[public libraries]] are promoting \"online storytimes\". There have also been major efforts to boost access to [[eBooks]]: by increasing the number of eBooks that people can borrow at any given time, by reassigning budgets to pay for electronic content,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2020/03/20/demand-e-books-rises-area-libraries|title=Demand For E-books Rises At Area Libraries|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"IFLA\" /> On March 24 the [[Internet Archive]] announced the creation of a \"National Emergency Library\" whereby it suspended the waitlists on 1.4m ebooks from their lending library \u2013 books that are not in the [[Public domain in the United States|Public domain in the USA]] \u2013 in order to ensure uninterrupted access to works books for educators and students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.archive.org/2020/03/24/announcing-a-national-emergency-library-to-provide-digitized-books-to-students-and-the-public/|title=Announcing a National Emergency Library to Provide Digitized Books to Students and the Public|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Internet Archive Blogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/internet-archive-offers-thousands-of-copyrighted-books-for-free-online/|title=Internet Archive offers 1.4 million copyrighted books for free online|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=2020-03-28|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The announcement strongly criticised by the [[publishing industry]].<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe Library of the [[National Congress of Argentina]] created activities including public readings and delivery of selected artworks through [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/cultura/2020/03/18/biblioteca-del-congreso-todas-las-actividades-online-durante-la-pandemia-del-coronavirus/|title=Biblioteca del Congreso: todas las actividades online durante la pandemia del coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n====[[Museums]]====\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cThis year, the paint has more time to dry.\u201d<br> \nA statement from the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] announcing a delay to the [[Archibald Prize]] portraiture exhibition until after the health crisis, \"when art will be needed more than ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/paint-has-more-time-to-dry-archibald-prize-delayed-20200321-p54ck2.html|title='Paint has more time to dry': Archibald Prize delayed|date=21 March 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMany websites were rapidly updated to focus on digital resources. In mid-March the [[Museum Computer Network]] published an extensive \"Guide to Virtual Museum Resources, E-Learning, and Online Collections\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcn.edu/a-guide-to-virtual-museum-resources/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Virtual Museum Resources|date=2020-03-15|website=MCN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Lists also were published of fine-art museums with existing interactive services (notably those already \"partners\" of [[Google Arts & Culture]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/547919/2500-virtual-museum-tours-google-arts-culture/|title=2,500 Museums You Can Now Visit Virtually|date=2020-03-16|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philbrook Museum of Art]]'s rapid relaunch their website in late-March \u2013 in order \"for us all to spend some time practicing social distancing and experiencing the #MuseumFromHome\" \u2013 was described as a model example of how an institution could \"Reorganise, Reuse and Rethink\" its activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/reorganise-reuse-get-creative-and-relaunch-lessons-from-philbrook/|title=Reorganise, Reuse, Rethink and Relaunch - Lessons from Philbrook|date=2020-03-21|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Other specific examples included [[Europeana]] publishing a digital gallery of images relating to the theme of [[handwashing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.europeana.eu/en/galleries/washing-your-hands|title=Washing your hands|website=www.europeana.eu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Museum of New Zealand]] publishing a \"little page of calm\" (a reference to the 1997 bestselling book ''[[Little book of calm]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tepapa.govt.nz/discover-collections/read-watch-play/little-page-calm|title=The little page of calm|date=2020-03-16|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa, Wellington, NZ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nAmerican art museum [[Indianapolis Contemporary]] has announced permanent closure as a result of the financial strain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indcontemporary.org/press-release/ic-to-close |title=I/C Board Announces Plans To Close \u2014 Indianapolis Contemporary |publisher=Indcontemporary.org |date=2020-02-04 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n====[[Music]]====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the music industry}}\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cIt is very hard financially and if you have lost the momentum you have built up over time,\" ... But this is also an ideal time for artists to do what it is they are supposed to be doing: create art.\"<br>Musician and performer, [[Tim Minchin]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cooper|first=Nathanael|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/for-musicians-collapse-of-touring-industry-opens-door-to-creativity-20200403-p54gpx.html|title=For musicians, collapse of touring industry opens door to creativity|date=5 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\nMany musicians delayed the releases of [[Album|albums]] due to the pandemic (including [[Lady Gaga]] and [[Willie Nelson]]),<ref name=\"rstone1\">{{cite web |last1=Leight |first1=Elias |title=They Were Going to Be Spring's Biggest Albums -- Until COVID-19 Hit |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/album-delays-caused-by-covid-19-973870/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> some moved up the release dates of their upcoming albums (including [[Dua Lipa]] and [[Sufjan Stevens]]),<ref name=\"sgum1\">{{cite web |last1=Rettig |first1=James |title=HAIM, Dua Lipa, Willie Nelson, & Sufjan Stevens Among Artists Moving Album Release Dates Amid Pandemic |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077667/dua-lipa-willie-nelson-sufjan-stevens-among-artists-moving-album-release-dates-amid-pandemic/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> and others (including [[Nine Inch Nails]] and [[Phish]]) released new albums with little or no notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farokhmanesh |first1=Megan |title=Nine Inch Nails just released two new albums for free |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/26/21195266/nine-inch-nails-new-albums-just-ghosts-v-vi-free-download |website=The Verge |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Phish to Debut New Album 'Sigma Oasis' During April 1st Livestream |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/phish-new-album-sigma-oasis-976437/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> In the middle of March, [[Bob Dylan]] released a single 17 minute new song called \"[[Murder Most Foul (song)|Murder Most Foul]]\", his first piece of original material in eight years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McFadyen|first=Matthew|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/murder-most-foul-bob-dylan-s-surprise-song-for-the-viral-age-20200330-p54f8z.html|title=Murder Most Foul: Bob Dylan's surprise song for the viral age|date=30 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020 Eurovision Song Contest]], set to take place in May in [[Rotterdam]], [[Netherlands]], was canceled by the [[European Broadcasting Union]] in March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official EBU statement & FAQ on Eurovision 2020 cancellation |url=https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation |website=Eurovision.tv |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> This marked the first time the annual contest had not taken place since its first installment in 1956.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eurovision Song Contest Canceled Because of Coronavirus |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eurovision-song-contest-cancelled-because-coronavirus-1282660 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIndividually and collectively, [[musicians]] organised online performances, often with musical sections referencing the fact of social isolation or home-quarantine, via their own social media platforms. Some were especially planned and prepared; some were impromptu. For example, cellist [[Yo-Yo Ma|YoYo Ma]] performed \"Going Home\" by [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]], the [[West Australian Symphony Orchestra]] renamed themselves the \"West Australian Social Distancing Orchestra\" and played a re-arranged version of ''[[Bol\u00e9ro]]'' by [[Maurice Ravel]] and an amateur choir gathered the contributions of more than 1000 people from 18 countries to create a video performance of \u201cClose To You\u201d by [[The Carpenters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HezxInuN1YA|title=Couch Choir - (They Long To Be) Close To You|last=|first=|date=22 March 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Many musicians, singers and songwriters adapted to the crisis by turning to teaching online as there was both a sudden increase in people wanting to learn instruments, and a drop in paid public performance opportunities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lamond|first=Scott|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-cant-stop-the-music-as-online-lessons-in-demand/12089060|title=Coronavirus sees ARIA-winning musicians turn online teachers as students flock to lessons|date=26 March 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral special remote-participation [[concerts]] were organised to provide entertainment to the public, and to raise awareness methods to combat the virus, notably [[physical distancing]]. The [[iHeart Living Room Concert for America]] concert (hosted by [[Elton John]]) was broadcast on American TV and radio, while ''[[Together at Home]]'' is a \"virtual concert series\". The quickly organised \"Instagram Live Music Festival\"''Isol Aid'' (a reference to [[Live Aid]]) of 72 Australian bands was broadcast on the weekend of 21\u201322 March. Each artist performed from wherever the were [[Isolation (health care)|self isolating]] and \"... play a 20-minute set streamed live on their Instagram accounts, and then tag-team the next artist to play\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/isol-aid-instagram-live-music-festival-coronavirus-covid-19/12072202|title=Isol-Aid is a stacked Aussie livestreaming music festival that's happening this weekend|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-03-19|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://linktr.ee/isolaidfestival|title=@isolaidfestival|website=Linktree|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>.\n\n====[[Performing arts]]====\nNew (or a newly expanded range) free [[online streaming]] of previously recorded theatrical performances was provided by many institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Convery|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/20/livestreaming-schedule-music-art-literature-and-events-from-australia-and-beyond|title=Livestreaming schedule: music, art, literature and events from Australia and beyond|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Rawson|first2=Sharnee|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> For example, the [[Metropolitan Opera]] of New York broadcast a new opera each evening, including an entire [[Ring Cycle]] performed during the 2010\u201312 seasons, via their own app,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/in-wake-of-season-cancellation-metropolitan-opera-continues-free-streaming-series-with-a-week-of-wagner|title=In Wake of Season Cancellation, Metropolitan Opera Continues Free Streaming Series With a Week of Wagner|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Playbill]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] company of Moscow made available six of their recorded performances via [[YouTube]] for 24 hours each.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/03/27/spend-an-evening-at-the-bolshoi-a69775|title=Spend an Evening at the Bolshoi|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=The Moscow Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-russia-bolshoi-idUSKBN21E35D|title=Russia's Bolshoi Theater goes online as coronavirus curbs public life|date=2020-03-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en}}</ref> The [[West End theatre|West End]] production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows (musical)|The Wind in the Willows]]'' was also streamed for UK residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/theatre-and-arts/wind-in-the-willows-streaming-west-end|title=You Can Screen The West End's Wind In The Willows Online For Free|date=2020-03-18|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIndividual actors, such as [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[Sam Neill]], entertained from isolation in order to \"...be in this together and that this has to take the form of being apart\", as Neill described his contribution of [[comedic relief]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Craven|first=Peter|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/movies/when-the-going-got-tough-sam-neill-got-out-his-ukulele-20200330-p54fd8.html|title=When the going got tough, Sam Neill got out his ukulele|date=1 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Stewart, a trained Shakespearian actor, broadcast himself reading one [[Shakespearean sonnet|sonnet]] each day via [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/books-and-poetry/patrick-stewart-is-treating-twitter-to-one-shakespearan-sonnet-a-day-during-lockdown|title=Patrick Stewart Is Treating Twitter To One Shakespeare Sonnet A Day During Lockdown|date=2020-03-25|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n====[[Radio]]====\n[[SiriusXM]] offered free streaming of their subscription-based radio service from April 2 to May 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=SiriusXM Offers Free Streaming Amid Social Distancing |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/siriusxm-offers-free-streaming-amid-social-distancing/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[NPR]] continued to produce new episodes of its ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' quiz [[panel show]], although it was no longer recorded in front of a live audience, and live tapings in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] and [[Atlanta]] were canceled .<ref>{{cite web |last1=News |first1=N. P. R. |title=A message from NPR on programming |url=https://news.wbfo.org/post/message-npr-programming |website=news.wbfo.org |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Taping of NPR's 'Wait, Wait' quiz show at Shea's postponed |url=https://buffalonews.com/2020/03/17/taping-of-npr-wait-wait-quiz-show-at-sheas-postponed/ |website=The Buffalo News |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en-us |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ruggieri |first1=Melissa |title=NPR cancels Thursday live taping of 'Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me' at the Fox Theatre |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/music/npr-cancels-thursday-live-taping-wait-wait-don-tell-the-fox-theatre/wb24HTGK9GaKFgd64XnK2O/ |website=Atlanta Journal-Constitution |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=english}}</ref>\n\n==Impacts==\n===Budgets and employment===\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDue to the closures, revenues for cultural organisations reliant on ticket sales were expected to cause devastating effects upon revenues, with consequent impacts upon organisational staffing, and on independent artists and professionals. This is due to the fact that the arts and culture is a sector of national economies characterised by particularly a high proportion of self-employment.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/arts-council-england-emergency-relief-fund-1814829|title=Arts Council England Has Launched a $190 Million Emergency Relief Package for Creative Organizations and Artists|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> For example, by the 20th of March the [[Cirque du Soleil]] had [[laid off]] 95% of its workforce and closed [[traveling circus]] performances operating in seven countries,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/cirque-de-soleil-canada-coronavirus-staff-fired-1493386|title=Cirque du Soleil lays off 95 percent of its workforce after coronavirus forces closure of all its shows globally|last=Cole|first=Brendan|date=2020-03-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The world commercial art market declined 5% in 2019 compared to the previous year, and is expected to decline further in 2020 \u2013 with 6 of the world's 10 largest auction houses operating exclusively in China. Major art fairs such as [[Hong Kong Arts Festival]] and [[Art Basel]] were cancelled, furthering a shift towards online purchases and the creation of VIP \"online viewing rooms\" rather than physical displaying at [[art auctions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-coronavirus-pandemic-corona-panic-is-shaking-up-worlds-global-art-market-starting-in-hong-kong/a-52651815|title=The coronavirus is shaking up the world's art market in unexpected ways|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|website=DW.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nArts and culture sector budgetary and employment reports from individual countries included:<br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. [[Opera Australia]] \u2013 the nation's largest [[performing arts]] company \u2013 temporarily stood down nearly all its staff<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/exit-stage-left-opera-australia-leads-arts-shutdown-20200325-p54dq1|title=Exit stage left: Opera Australia leads arts shutdown|date=2020-03-26|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> amid speculation it would also need to sell major assets in order to avoid [[bankruptcy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/opera-australia-looks-to-sell-offs-to-stay-afloat-20200316-p54ai2.html|title=Opera Australia looks to sell-offs to stay afloat|last=Galvin|first=Nick|date=2020-03-16|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> By the 23rd of March, 255,000 cultural events had been cancelled with an estimated revenue loss of $A280 million, self reported through the crowdsourced website ILostMyGig.net.au.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-what-the-latest-stimulus-measures-mean-for-australian-artists-and-arts-organisations-134233|title=Coronavirus: what the latest stimulus measures mean for Australian artists and arts organisations|last=Caust|first=Jo|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. In March, when many institutions closed for the first time since [[WWII]], the state-funded museum sector had been valued at \u20ac27 billion or 1.6% of national GDP \u2013 slightly smaller than the agriculture sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/coronavirus-l-impatto-negativo-chiusure-musei-che-valgono-l-16percento-pil-AC4pFCMB|title=Coronavirus, l'impatto negativo delle chiusure sui musei (che valgono l'1,6% del Pil)|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. As the pandemic spread and closures became the standard not the exception, institutions started publishing expected revenue shortfall calculations, began to fire staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AMTransparency/status/1242869675425443840|title=This will be a thread for tracking museum layoff news.|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|publisher=Art + Museum Transparency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> For example: the [[Metropolitan opera]] expects to lose $60m in revenue;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woolfe|first=Zachary|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/arts/music/metropolitan-opera-coronavirus.html|title=Metropolitan Opera Cancels Season Over Virus and Faces $60 Million Loss|date=2020-03-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the [[Metropolitan Museum]] expects to lose $100m in revenue with likely layoffs;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/arts/design/met-museum-coronavirus-closure.html|title=Met Museum Prepares for $100 Million Loss and Closure Till July|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and SFMOMA [[furlough]]ed 300 staff in the expectation of a 40% decrease in revenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13877653/sfmoma-to-lay-off-or-furlough-over-300-museum-staff|title=SFMOMA to Lay Off or Furlough Over 300 Museum Staff|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=2020-03-27|website=[[KQED]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Science Museum of Minnesota]] expected to lose $15m in revenue over three months. Consequently, it \"temporarily\" [[laid off]] most of its staff in an announcement via a [[Google Hangouts]] videocall in late March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-science-museum-children-s-museum-lay-off-most-staff-in-wake-of-covid-19-outbreak/569063662/|title=Science Museum of Minnesota, Children's Museum temporarily lay off most staff in wake of COVID-19|website=Star Tribune|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Meanwhile, staff across the museum began to unionise, even though \"[[Social distancing]] orders prevent the in-person meetings required to sign the cards required to file for union elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tinyletter.com/artandmuseumtransparency/letters/art-museum-transparency-newsletter-2-march-2020|title=Art + Museum Transparency Newsletter #2 -- March 2020|last=|first=|date=2020-03-26|website=artandmuseumtransparency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Financial relief ===\nWith the extensive financial disruption across all areas of the economy, many governments announced [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] and [[Bailout|economic bailout]] packages which included specific resources for the arts and cultural sectors. Equally, various [[charities]] and industry bodies raised funds to support their sector.\n\nArts and culture sector financial stimulus packages from individual countries included:\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. petition of over 50 arts and culture organisations (including peak bodies from the music, dance, visual arts, museums, writers' and indigenous arts groups) requested a financial aid package \"...to a value of 2% of the $111.7 billion [cultural and creative] industry\" and requesting the Prime Minister \"...issue a public statement recognising the value of our industry to all Australians\" and noting that the industry had not yet recovered from the impact of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://visualarts.net.au/news-opinion/2020/creative-industry-unites/|title=Creative industry unites to secure Australia's cultural life|website=NAVA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The library professional association [[Australian Library and Information Association|ALIA]] announced a \"relief fund\" of payments up to $500 to cover the cost of essential expenses for its members \"...experiencing a reduction in income as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alia.org.au/alia-covid-19-relief-fund|title=ALIA COVID-19 Relief Fund|last=|first=|date=2020-04-03|website=www.alia.org.au|publisher=Australian Library and Information Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. The minister for culture [[Franck Riester]] announced that employees of cultural institutions currently receiving unemployment benefits calculated over 12 months will see the confinement period withdrawn from the calculation <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.francemusique.fr/actualite-musicale/coronavirus-le-gouvernement-annonce-des-mesures-pour-les-intermittents-du-spectacle-82453 |title=Coronavirus : le gouvernement annonce des mesures pour les intermittents du spectacle |language=fr|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. The minister for culture [[Monika Gr\u00fctters]] declared that \"artists are not only indispensable, but also vital, especially now.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/german-bailout-50-billion-1815396|title=Germany Has Rolled Out a Staggering \u20ac50 Billion Aid Package For Small Businesses That Boosts Artists and Galleries\u2014and Puts Other Countries to Shame|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The statement was made while announcing a \u20ac50 billion stimulus package for small business and freelancers \u2013 explicitly including the creative sectors.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. The Swedish Minister of Culture [[Amanda Lind]] presented a 1 billion [[Swedish krona|SEK]] support package for sports and culture, where 500 million SEK was earmarked for culture (not including government agencies like the [[Royal Dramatic Theatre]] and [[Kungliga Operan]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=En miljard i akut st\u00f6d till kultur och idrott|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/coronaviruset/en-miljard-i-akut-stod-till-kultur-och-idrott/|publisher=Expressen|access-date=2020-03-25|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. [[The Film and TV Charity]] created an emergency relief fund in order to \"provide emergency short-term relief to active workers and freelancers who have been directly affected by the closure of productions across the UK\", with an initial donation of \u00a31m from [[Netflix]] and by \u00a3500,000 from the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bfi-uk-film-and-tv-charity-set-up-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-with-1m-donation-from-netflix-1202890966/|title=BFI & UK Film And TV Charity Set Up Covid-19 Emergency Relief Fund With \u00a31M Donation From Netflix|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=2020-03-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bbc-donates-to-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-1202894127/|title=BBC Joins Netflix In Making $600,000 Donation To Coronavirus Emergency Relief Fund|last=Kanter|first=Jake|date=2020-03-27|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Museums Association]] called upon the UK government to divert \u00a3120m that was intended for the [[Festival of Britain|Festival of Britain 2022]] to bail out museums in financial distress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/17032020-museum-closures-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Museums and galleries close as coronavirus emergency intensifies|last=Kendall Adams|first=Geraldine|date=17 March 2020|website=Museums Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> [[Arts Council England]] announced \u00a3160 million would be made available for arts organisations, including \u00a350 million for organisations it does not usually fund and \u00a320 million for individual and freelance artists.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Paul Hamlyn Foundation]] announced that the usual competitive selection process for their \"Award for Artists\" program would be removed, and that instead of ten awards of \u00a360,000, each of the more than 100 previously nominated eligible applicants would automatically receive \u00a310,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phf.org.uk/news/1-million-awarded-to-visual-artists-and-composers-in-the-uk/|title=\u00a31 million awarded to visual artists and composers in the UK|date=2020-04-06|website=Paul Hamlyn Foundation|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A petition was begun by the [[American Alliance of Museums]] to request that the museum sector was included in any future [[economic stimulus]] from the United States government,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congressweb.com/AAM/67|title=Tell Congress: Include Museums in COVID-19 Economic Relief|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> while the Metropolitan museum was more specific \u2013 requesting $4 billion for at-risk museums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/metropolitan-museum-of-art-congress-1813665|title=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Is Calling on the US Government to Bail Out At-Risk Museums With $4 Billion in Aid|date=2020-03-24|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn late March the United States federal government announced a $2 trillion economic stimulus package. It included: \"$75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] and $75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], which can pass on the money to institutions that need it. Another $50 million was designated to the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]], which distributes funds to museums and libraries.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/arts/coronavirus-arts-bailout.html|title=Arts Groups, Facing Their Own Virus Crisis, Get a Piece of the Stimulus|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> While a common argument in the USA against the cultural sector receiving stimulus funding was that \"Arts groups may be 'nice,' but they\u2019re far from 'necessary.'\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Copyright ===\nAcademic librarians in the United States made public statements on the applicability and importance of the role of the [[fair use]] copyright exception for \"Emergency Remote Teaching & Research\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/10baTITJbFRh7D6dHVVvfgiGP2zqaMvm0EHHZYf2cBRk/mobilebasic?urp=gmail_link|title=Public Statement: Fair Use & Emergency Remote Teaching & Research|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Cornell University Library]] made the advice explicit, noting in a new official library policy recommending, \"...that faculty may scan course material in amounts that may exceed customary fair use limits under normal circumstances. Fair use provides flexibility to permit faculty scan broader amounts of course material than normal during these exigent circumstances.\" and noted that library staff were no longer allowed to work on-site and therefore not able to scan materials on behalf of teaching staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://copyright.cornell.edu/covid|title=COVID-19 & Copyright at Cornell {{!}} Copyright Information Center|website=copyright.cornell.edu|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> [[File:National_Emergency_Library.png|thumb|right|the \"National Emergency Library\" of the Internet Archive on 24 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/nationalemergencylibrary|title=National Emergency Library : Free Texts : Free Download, Borrow and Streaming : Internet Archive|last=|first=|date=|website=archive.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>]]\nThe ''National Emergency Library'' of the Internet Archive \u2013 which suspended waitlists for access to digitised in-copyright books citing the justification of Fair Use during the pandemic \u2013 was criticised as \"piracy masquerading as public service\" and copyright infringement, especially by the [[Association of American Publishers]] and [[Authors Guild]]<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/books/internet-archive-emergency-library.html|title='Emergency' Online Library Draws Ire of Some Authors|date=2020-03-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> as well as drawing public critique from several noted authors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/internet-archive-national-emergency-library-controversy.html|title=The Internet Archive Started an \"Emergency\" Online Library. Authors Are Furious.|last=Hampton|first=Rachelle|date=2020-04-01|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The Internet Archive defended its program by emphasising that: the collection consisted primarily of older in-copyright works without digital surrogates; it is a temporary program; authors can chose to opt-out; and the works are chosen for the educational not commercial value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.archive.org/2020/03/30/internet-archive-responds-why-we-released-the-national-emergency-library/|title=Internet Archive responds: Why we released the National Emergency Library {{!}} Internet Archive Blogs|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/controversy-surrounds-national-emergency-library-180974554/|title=Why the National Emergency Library Is So Controversial|last=Machemer|first=Theresa|website=Smithsonian Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nThe libraries of universities and of the [[National Research Council (Italy)|National Research Council]] in Italy petitioned [[academic publishers]] to provide temporary [[open access]] to publications in order to medical staff, scientific researchers, and the general public access during the national emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centumcellae.it/cronaca/appello-per-il-diritto-di-accesso-alla-conoscenza-scientifica-in-stato-di-emergenza/|title=APPELLO PER IL DIRITTO DI ACCESSO ALLA CONOSCENZA SCIENTIFICA IN STATO DI EMERGENZA|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=Centumcellae|language=it-IT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n[[LeVar Burton]], host of ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'', announced his desire to perform live-streamed readings of books for his podcast ''LeVar Reads'' but that copyright law was unclear as to whether this was allowed. [[Neil Gaiman]] replied to Burton via Twitter, giving him permission to read any of his works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/939vjv/please-dont-sue-levar-burton-for-reading-soothing-stories-to-scared-children|title=Please Don't Sue LeVar Burton for Reading Soothing Stories to Scared Children|last=Cole|first=Samantha|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious online training workshops were organised for cultural heritage to learn about relevant risks and [[Copyright exceptions|exceptions to copyright]] when providing online services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/open-glam/copyright-open-access-for-glams-in-the-age-of-covid-3a35e67f7a1|title=Copyright & Open Access for GLAMs in the age of COVID-19|last=|first=|date=2020-03-24|website=Medium|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Equally, [[digital strategy]] workshops<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usingdata.com/usingdata/2020/3/19/free-strategy-workshops-march-23-april-3|title=Free strategy workshops March 23 \u2013 April 3|website=Usingdata|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and live Q&A sessions with experts were organised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AAMers/status/1242798776655413249|title=What #COVID19 questions do you want to pose to the museum field? Comment below or DM us to include it in our #MuseumsDiscussCOVID19 Tweet chat! TODAY 3-4 pm|publisher=American Alliance of Museums|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n=== New cultural works ===\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nWith thorough and global disruption society to an unprecedented level, there is the expectation of many and diverse cultural works created which reference or are inspired by the pandemic and its effects. One gallery director said: \"There will definitely be an explosion in new material.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dye|first=Josh|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/perplexing-and-confusing-art-gallery-of-nsw-director-grapples-with-coronavirus-crisis-20200327-p54emd.html|title='Perplexing and confusing': Art Gallery of NSW director grapples with coronavirus crisis|date=28 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{CC-notice|cc=by4|url=https://www.ifla.org/covid-19-and-libraries|author(s)=[[IFLA]]}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage}}\n[[Category:2020 in arts]]\n[[Category:Cultural heritage]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|arts]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:IFLA\u2192International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions(2);", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_the_arts_and_cultural_heritage"}
{"title_page": "Coitus reservatus", "text_new": "'''Coitus reservatus''' (''[[Sexual intercourse|coitus]]'', \"sexual intercourse, union\" + ''reservatus'', \"reserved, saved\"),<ref>Cassell's ''Compact Latin Dictionary'', Dell Publishing Co. Inc., 1963</ref> also known as '''sexual continence''', is a form of sexual intercourse in which the penetrative partner does not attempt to [[Ejaculation|ejaculate]] within the receptive partner, but instead attempts to remain at the [[Human sexual response cycle#Plateau phase|plateau phase]] of intercourse for as long as possible, avoiding the seminal emission. It is distinct from [[death grip syndrome]] wherein the male has no volition in his emissionless state.<ref>Levin, Roy J. \"Male Sexual Arousal and Orgasms\u2014New Enigmas of Their Activation.\" Current Sexual Health Reports 10.3 (2018): 76-78.</ref>\n\n[[Alice Stockham]] coined the term ''karezza'', derived from the Italian word \"carezza\" meaning \"caress\", to describe coitus reservatus, but the idea was already in practice at the [[Oneida Community]]. [[Alan Watts]] believed, in error, that karezza was a Persian word.<ref>{{cite book |last=Watts |first=Alan W. |title=Nature, Man and Woman |url=https://archive.org/details/naturemanwoman00watt |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/naturemanwoman00watt/page/172 172] |year=1970 |publisher=Random House Inc. Vintage Books Edition |lccn=58-8266 }}</ref> The concept of karezza is loosely akin to [[maithuna]] in [[Tantra|Hindu Tantra]] and [[Sahaja]] in Hindu [[Yoga]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Coomaraswami |first=Ananda K.|title=The Dance of Shiva |page=124 |publisher=The Noonday Press Inc. |year=1957 |location=New York City |lccn=56-12296}}</ref>\n\nControl of ejaculation is a key aspect of [[Taoist sexual practices]] (known as \"cai Yin pu Yang\" and \"cai Yang pu Yin\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/GESUND/ARCHIV/SEN/CH23.HTM|title=Human Sexuality: An Encyclopedia: T|last=Pauly|first=Ira B.|date=2013-05-23|publisher=Humboldt-Universit\u00e4t zu Berlin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523194332/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/GESUND/ARCHIV/SEN/CH23.HTM|archive-date=2013-05-23|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-06-18}}</ref>\n\n== Practice of Karezza and Tantric (sexual) continence ==\n\nStockham writes, \"... Karezza signifies 'to express affection in both words and action,' and while it fittingly denotes the union that is the outcome of deepest human affection, love's consummation, it is used technically throughout this work to designate a controlled sexual union.\" So that in practice, according to Stockham, it is more than just self-control, but mutual control where the penetrative partner helps the receptive partner and vice versa. According to Stockham this is the key to overcoming many difficulties encountered in trying to control sexual expression on an individual basis.{{sfn |Stockham |1896 |p=22}}\nStockham's contribution was to apply this same philosophy of [[Edging (sexual practice)|orgasm control]] to women as much as to men. A form of [[birth control]], the technique also prolongs sexual pleasure to the point of achieving mystical ecstasy, according to [[John William Lloyd|J. William Lloyd]], a practitioner of Karezza, whose own experience of [[cosmic consciousness]] appears in  ''Cosmic Consciousness'', a book written  by the Canadian psychiatrist [[Richard Maurice Bucke|Richard M. Bucke]], a friend of the American poet [[Walt Whitman]].<ref>Bucke, Richard Maurice, M. D. ''Cosmic Consciousness'', p. 284, Citadel Press, 1961, {{ISBN|0-8065-0211-8}}</ref> In this practice,  orgasm is separated from ejaculation, making possible enjoyment of the pleasure of sexual intercourse without experiencing seminal ejaculation, while still experiencing orgasm.\n\nSome would have the principles of karezza applied to masturbation, whereby a person attempts to delay orgasm as long as possible to prolong pleasure in a process known as \"orgasmic brinkmanship\", \"surfing\", or \"edging,\" but this is different from the heterosexual practice of \"karezza\".<ref>Ruth Marie Griffith ''Born Again Bodies'', p. 92, [[University of California Press]], 2004 {{ISBN|978-0-520-24240-1}}</ref> In Latin literature, this is known as ''coitus sine ejaculatione seminis''.<ref>Lloyd, J. William ''The Karezza Method'' Health Research, 1964, Mokelumne Hill, California</ref>\n\nOne purpose of karezza is the maintenance, and indeed, intensification of desire and enjoyment of sexual pleasure within the context of  relationships. According to Stockham, it takes from two weeks to a month for the body to recover from ejaculation ... \"Unless procreation is desired, let the final propagative orgasm be entirely avoided\".{{sfn |Stockham |1896 |p=25}} Stockham advocated that the 'honeymoon period' of a relationship could be maintained in perpetuity by limiting the frequency of ejaculations, or, preferably avoiding them entirely.{{sfn |Stockham |1896 |p=15}}\n\nKalman Andras Oszlar writes, \"Inasmuch as sexual togetherness is not limited into the physical world and does not mean quick wasting of sexual energies, by this we give free way to higher dimensions in the relationship.\" Affected by this, we may get into the state of flow, and in the course of this, the couple charges up with energy, while \u2013 with focused attention ([[Dh\u0101ra\u1e47\u0101]]) \u2013 the couple is submerging in that in which they are having pleasure. This state of mind is connected with the achieved beneficial effects by tantric restraint and transformation. At first, the definition of positive philosophy was defined by [[Mih\u00e1ly Cs\u00edkszentmih\u00e1lyi]], and since then it is referred beyond the professional line. According to the professor, the flow experience is an entirely focused and a motivationally intensified experience where in the course of this people can entirely focus and properly command their feelings for the best performance or learning.\n\n===General===\nThere is a slight difference between karezza and coitus reservatus.  In coitus reservatus, unlike karezza, a woman can enjoy a prolonged orgasm while a man exercises self-control.<ref name=\"Urban 1949\">{{cite web | last=Urban | first=Rudolf von | title=Sex perfection and marital happiness | publisher=Dial Press | year=1949 | oclc=688412035 | url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/api/volumes/oclc/14678823.html | access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n\nLike [[coitus interruptus]], coitus reservatus is not a reliable form of preventing a [[sexually transmitted disease]], as the penis leaks [[pre-ejaculate]] prior to ejaculation, which may contain all of the same infectious viral particles and bacteria as the [[semen]]. Although studies have not found sperm in pre-ejaculate fluid,<ref>{{cite journal\n|title=Researchers find no sperm in pre-ejaculate fluid\n|journal = Contraceptive Technology Update\n|volume = 14 | issue = 10 |pages=154\u2013156 |date=October 1993 | pmid = 12286905 }}\n</ref><ref name=\"pre-e study\">{{cite journal\n|last=Zukerman |first=Z. |author2=Weiss D.B. Orvieto R.\n|title=Short Communication: Does Preejaculatory Penile Secretion Originating from Cowper's Gland Contain Sperm?\n|journal = Journal of Assisted Reproduction and Genetics\n| volume = 20 | issue = 4 |pages=157\u2013159 |date=April 2003 | pmid = 12762415 |doi = 10.1023/A:1022933320700 | pmc=3455634}}\n</ref> the method is also unreliable for [[contraception]] because of the difficulty of controlling ejaculation beyond the point of no return. Additionally, it is possible for pre-ejaculate fluid to collect sperm from a previous ejaculation, leading to pregnancy even when performed correctly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Withdrawal Method |work=Planned Parenthood |date=March 2004 | url =http://www.plannedparenthood.com/health-topics/birth-control/withdrawal-pull-out-method-4218.htm |accessdate=2008-03-28 }}</ref>\n\n===Views on ''coitus reservatus''===\nThe [[Oneida Community]], founded in the 19th century by [[John Humphrey Noyes]], experimented with coitus reservatus which was then called '''male continence''' in a religiously [[Christianity|Christian]] [[communalism|communalist]] environment. The experiment lasted for about a quarter of a century and then Noyes went on to create Oneida silverware and establish the Oneida Silver Co. that grew into [[Oneida Limited]].{{sfn |Ellis |1910 |p=553}}  Noyes identified three functions of the sexual organs: the urinary, the propagative, and the amative. Noyes believed in the separation of the amative from the propagative, and he put amative sexual intercourse on the same footing with other ordinary forms of social interchange. Sexual intercourse as Noyes defines it is the insertion of the penis into the vagina; ejaculation is not a requirement for sexual intercourse.<ref name=\"Noyes 1872\">{{cite book |title=Male continence |website=Syracuse University Library - Department of Special Collections - Oneida Community Collection |authorlink=John Humphrey Noyes |first=John Humphrey |last=Noyes |archiveurl=https://iiif.lib.harvard.edu/manifests/view/drs:2577486$1i |archivedate=2017-11-03 |url-status=live |year=1877 |orig-year=1872 |location=Oneida, NY |publisher=Office of the American Socialist |oclc=786280936 |url=https://library.syr.edu/digital/collections/m/MaleContinence-51k/}}</ref>\n\nEnglish novelist [[Aldous Huxley]], in his last novel ''Island'' wrote that Maithuna, the Yoga of Love is \"the same as what [[Roman Catholicism]] means by ''coitus reservatus''.\"<ref>Huxley, Aldous ''Island, Harper & Row, 1962''</ref> Getting to the point by discussing ''coitus reservatus'', Alan W. Watts in ''Nature, Man and Woman'' notes: \"...I would like to see someone make a case for the idea that the [[Apostles]] really did hand down an inner tradition to the Church, and that through all these centuries the Church has managed to guard it from the public eye. If so, it has remained far more secret and [[esotericism|\"esoteric\"]] than in any of the other great spiritual traditions of the world, so much so that its existence is highly doubtful...\"<ref>\"Watts, Alan W. ''Nature, Man and Woman, Ch 7, Pantheon Books Inc. 1958''</ref> The Welsh writer [[Norman Lewis (author)|Norman Lewis]], in his celebrated account of life in [[Naples]] in 1944, claimed that [[Saint Roch|San Rocco]] was the [[patron saint]] of coitus reservatus:  \"I recommended him to drink -- as the locals did -- [[Marsala wine|marsala]] with the yolk of eggs stirred into it, and to wear a medal of San Rocco, patron of coitus reservatus, which could be had in any religious-supplies shop\".<ref name=\"Lewis 2005 p. \">{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Norman |title=Naples '44 : a World War II diary of occupied Italy |publisher=Carroll & Graf |location=New York |year=2005 |isbn=9781480433250 |oclc=854852494 }}</ref> The psychologist [[Havelock Ellis]] writes: \"''Coitus Reservatus'', \u2013 in which intercourse is maintained even for very long periods, during which a woman may orgasm several times while the penetrative partner succeeds in holding back orgasm \u2013 so far from being injurious to a woman, is probably the form of coitus which gives her the maximum gratification and relief\".{{sfn|Ellis|1910|p=552}}\n\n=== Catholic Church and Coitus Reservatus ===\nThe Catholic Church does allow ''coitus reservatus'':\n\n* In [[Moral Theology (Liguori)]], St. [[Alphonsus Liguori]] allows it in marriage, if mutual (when both spouses restrain themselves from orgasm).<ref>{{cite book|title=Innocent Ecstasy: How Christianity Gave America an Ethic of Sexual Pleasure|last=Gardell|first=Peter|page=14\u201316|year=1985|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York and Oxford|isbn=9780195365153|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=VV_GNSx-vy4C&dq=%22amplexus+reservatus%22&pg=PA14&lpg=PA16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Innocent Ecstasy, Updated Edition: How Christianity Gave America an Ethic of Sexual Pleasure|last=Gardell|first=Peter|page=22|year=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York and Oxford|isbn=9780190609429|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=EP7mDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT22&lpg=PT22&dq=liguori+%22amplexus+reservatus%22}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Liguori|first=Alphonsus|title=Theologiae Moralis|year=1748}}</ref>\n* [[Holy See]] allows this practice in volume number 44<ref>https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-44-1952-ocr.pdf page 548</ref> of [[Acta Apostolicae Sedis]]. It refers to it under the Latin term \"amplexus reservatus\" (reserved embrace): \"contra \u00abamplexum reservatum\u00bb nihil esset obiicendum\" - \"nothing is objectionable\", so it's allowed.\n* [[John F. Harvey]] OSFS confirmed and explained ''coitus reservatus''. The spouses should avoid undue frustration. They must not intend orgasm for either of them.<ref>{{cite book|title=International Review of Natural Family Planning|page=211\u2013212|year=1981|url=http://www.usccb.org/issues-and-action/marriage-and-family/natural-family-planning/what-is-nfp/science/upload/intl-review-nfp-1981-harvey-expressing-marital-love-during-fertile-phase.pdf}}</ref> If unintentionally one of them reaches the climax, then they must try to stimulate the other spouse to reach the climax, too.<ref>{{cite book|title=Difficult Moral Questions, Question 29: What sexual activity is permissible...|year=1997|last=Professor Grisez|first=Germain|publisher=Franciscan Press, Quincy University|location=Quincy, Illinois, USA|url=http://www.twotlj.org/G-3-29.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Living a Christian Life, Chapter 9: Marriage, Sexual Acts, and Family Life, Question E: What Sexual Acts Are Appropriate for Christians?|year=1992|last=Professor Grisez|first=Germain|publisher=Franciscan Press, Quincy University|location=Quincy, Illinois, USA|url=http://www.twotlj.org/G-2-9-E.html}}</ref><ref>See http://www.twotlj.org/grisez_collaborators.html for the team credentials, http://www.twotlj.org for \"Nihil obstat\" and \"Imprimatur\".</ref>\n\nThat differs from how one author uses the same term \"amplexus reservatus\" for non-penetrative, rubbing-only sex.<ref name=\"Bullough 2001 p.\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of birth control|last=Bullough|first=Vern|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2001|isbn=9781576075333|location=Santa Barbara, Calif|page=|oclc=50174689}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=XuX-MGTZnJoC&pg=PA75&lpg=PA76&dq=reservatus |title = Encyclopedia of Birth Control|isbn = 9781576071816|last1 = Bullough|first1 = Vern L.|year = 2001}}</ref> The same source claims that ''coitus reservatus'' is subject to the same arguments as [[Coitus interruptus]], but with no citation at all.\n\nAnother author wrote that the Catholic Church condemned this practice.<ref>{{cite book|title=Enchiridion Symbolorum|last=Denzinger|first=Heinrich|publisher=Ignatius Press|year=2012|isbn=9780898707465|location=San Francisco, Calif|page=810}}</ref> However, that condemnation is contrary to official Catholic teaching referenced above.<br />\n\n== Rosicrucians ==\nThe [[AMORC]] [[Rosicrucians]] declare openly that they do not engage in sexual practices of an occult nature. This has been so since their First Imperator [[H. Spencer Lewis]], Ph. D. made it public knowledge.<ref>Lewis, H. Spencer ''Rosicrucian Manual'', p. 5, Supreme Grand Lodge of AMORC, 1978</ref> Their rival organization [[Fraternitas Rosae Crucis]] led by Dr. [[R. Swinburne Clymer]] engages in sexual practices for the sake of race regeneration. Dr. Clymer is completely opposed to the practice of Karezza or ''coitus reservatus'' and advocates instead a form of sex intercourse in which the couple experiences the orgasm at the same time.<ref>Clymer, R. Swinburne MD, ''The Mystery of Sex and Race Regeneration'', p. 223, The Philosophical Publishing Co., 1950</ref> The Secretary of the [[FUDOSI]] instead heartily approves the practice of Karezza to establish harmony in the family as well as in the world by preventing the waste and misuse of sex energy.<ref>Marc Lanval, editor, ''Lumi\u00e8re et Libert\u00e9'', Organe Officiel de la Ligue Belge de Propagande H\u00e9liophile, Octobre-Novembre 1933</ref>\n\nDr. [[Arnold Krumm-Heller]] established the [[Fraternitas Rosicruciana Antiqua]] (FRA), a Rosicrucian school in Germany with branches in South America, having the following formula of sexual conduct: \"Immissio Membri Virile In Vaginae Sine Ejaculatio Seminis\" (Introduce the penis in the vagina without ejaculating the semen). [[Samael Aun Weor]] experimented with that formula and developed the doctrine of ''[[The Perfect Matrimony]]''.\n\n== \"Dianism\" in Sex Magick == \n{{main|Dianism}}\nInspired by [[Ida Craddock]]'s work Heavenly Bridegrooms, American occultist [[C.F. Russell]] developed his own curriculum of [[sex magick]].<ref name=\"google.com2\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yFs3qoTFVz8C&pg=PA12|title=The Complete Magick Curriculum of the Secret Order G.B.G.|publisher=|isbn=9780738726748|last1=Culling|first1=Louis T.|last2=Weschcke|first2=Carl Llewellyn|date=8 September 2010}}</ref>  In the 1960s, disciple Louis T. Culling published these in two works entitled ''The Complete Magickal Curriculum of the Secret Order G.'.B.'.G.'.'' and ''Sex Magick''.<ref>{{Cite book|isbn=978-0-7387-1912-2|title=The Complete Magick Curriculum of the Secret Order G.B.G.: Being the Entire Study, Curriculum, Magick Rituals, and Initiatory Practices of the G.B.G (The Great Brotherhood of God)|author= Louis T. Culling, Carl Llewellyn Weschcke|date=8 September 2010|publisher=}}</ref>  The first two degrees are \"Alphaism and Dianism\".<ref name=\"google.com1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IoybRLX4jqIC&pg=PA244|title=Sexual Outlaw, Erotic Mystic|publisher=|isbn=9781609252960|last1=Chappell|first1=Vere|date=December 2010}}, Chappell, V. (2010). Sexual outlaw, erotic mystic: The essential Ida Craddock. San Francisco, CA: Red Wheel/Weiser.</ref><ref name=\"google.com2\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yFs3qoTFVz8C&pg=PA12|title=The Complete Magick Curriculum of the Secret Order G.B.G.|publisher=|isbn=9780738726748|last1=Culling|first1=Louis T.|last2=Weschcke|first2=Carl Llewellyn|date=8 September 2010}}</ref> Culling writes that Dianism is \"sexual congress without bringing it to climax\" and that each participant is to regard their partner not as a \"known earthly personality\" but as a \"visible manifestation of one's [[Holy Guardian Angel]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yFs3qoTFVz8C&pg=PA127|title=The Complete Magick Curriculum of the Secret Order G.B.G.: Being the Entire Study, Curriculum, Magick Rituals, and Initiatory Practices of the G.B.G (The Great Brotherhood of God)|last=Culling|first=Louis T.|last2=Weschcke|first2=Carl Llewellyn|publisher=Llewellyn Worldwide|year=2010|isbn=9780738726748|location=|pages=|language=en|oclc=793421982}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n[[Alice Bunker Stockham|Alice Stockham]] was taken to court and forced to give up teaching the practice of Karezza in the [[United States]]. Like many other sex reformers, Dr. Stockham was arrested by [[Anthony Comstock]].<ref>John P. Deveney ''Paschal B. Randolph'', p. 393, SUNY Press, 1997 {{ISBN|978-0-7914-3119-1}}</ref> He jailed for long terms a variety of spiritual marriage reformers including [[Paschal Beverly Randolph]] who had been a personal friend of [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref>Paschal B. Randolph ''Ravalette: The Rosicrucian's Story'', p. 64, Kessinger Publishing, 2005 {{ISBN|978-0-7661-9160-0}}</ref> [[Ida Craddock]] committed [[suicide in the United States|suicide]] after being repeatedly jailed for peddling [[pornography]].<ref>Vern L. Bullough ''Encyclopedia of Birth Control'', pp. 76-9, ABC-CLIO, 2001 {{ISBN|978-1-57607-181-6}}</ref> The [[Oneida Community]] was attacked in the press and Noyes was forced to flee to [[Canada]] due to a warrant being issued for his arrest on a [[statutory rape]] charge on June 22, 1879. From there, he advised others to follow [[St. Paul]]'s plan of either [[marriage]] or [[celibacy]], and to obey the [[Ten Commandments|commandments]] against [[adultery]] and [[fornication]].<ref>Patricia Gutek ''Visiting Utopian Communities'', p. 137, [[University of South Carolina Press]], 1998 {{ISBN|978-1-57003-210-3}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Human sexuality}}\n* [[Coitus interruptus]]\n* [[Coitus saxonicus]]\n* [[Eroto-comatose lucidity]]\n* [[Orgone]]\n* [[Sex magic]]\n* [[Venus Butterfly]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Ellis |first=Havelock |authorlink=Havelock Ellis |title=Studies in the psychology of sex. |website=Wellcome Library |url=http://wellcomelibrary.org/item/b18033659 |access-date=2017-11-03 |oclc=927688075 |year=1910 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=F.A. Davis |asin=B008499I5C |volume=Volume 6 Sex in Relation to Society |ref=harv}} <br/>Republished: {{cite book |last=Ellis |first=Havelock |title=Studies in the psychology of sex |publisher=Anboco |location=Dinslaken |year=2016 |isbn=9783736412088 |oclc=958563038 |volume=Volume 6 Sex in Relation to Society}}\n*{{cite web | last=Lloyd | first=J. William | title=The Karezza Method Index | website=Internet Sacred Text Archive Home | url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/sex/krz/index.htm | access-date=2017-11-03}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Lloyd\n|first=John William\n|authorlink=John William Lloyd\n|title=The Karezza Method or Magnetation: The Art of Connubial Love\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Rp3QveSUjEC\n|accessdate=7 March 2011\n|year=1931\n|publisher=Forgotten Books\n|isbn=978-1-60620-046-9}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Robinson\n|first=Marnia\n|authorlink=Marnia Robinson\n|title=Cupid's Poisoned Arrow: From Habit to Harmony in Sexual Relationships\n|url=\n|accessdate=\n|year=2009\n|publisher=North Atlantic Books\n|isbn=9781556438097}}\n*{{cite book| title=Karezza, Ethics of Marriage Index | website=Internet Sacred Text Archive Home | url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/sex/eom/index.htm | access-date=2017-11-03 |authorlink=Alice Bunker Stockham |first=Alice Bunker |last=Stockham |location=New York |publisher=R.F. Fenno and Co. |year=1896 |oclc=868004523 |ref=harv}} Also available as {{cite book |last=Stockham |first=Alice |title=Karezza Ethics of Marriage |publisher=Books on Demand |location=Norderstedt |year=2017 |isbn=9783744815086 |oclc=987572577}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Urban\n|first=Rudolf Von\n|authorlink=Rudolf von Urban\n|title=Sex perfection and marital happiness\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B8Q9AAAAYAAJ\n|accessdate=7 March 2011\n|year=1949\n|publisher=Dial Press}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | last=Antonyan | first=Christina | title=Healing with Sexual Relationships | website=Reuniting | date=2009-01-12 | url=http://www.reuniting.info/ | access-date=2017-11-03}}\n*{{cite web | title=natural sexuality| website=Wikischool | date=2016-03-03 | url=https://wikischool.org/natural_sexuality | access-date=2017-11-03}}\n*{{cite web | last=Noyes | first=John Humphrey | title=Male Continence Index | website=Internet Sacred Text Archive Home | url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/sex/mc/index.htm | access-date=2017-11-03}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.gnosiscentral.com/audioBooks-ThePerfectMatrimony.php | access-date=2017-11-03 |first=Samael Aun |last=Weor |title=The Perfect Matrimony}} (Audio Book)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coitus Reservatus}}\n[[Category:Sexual acts]]\n[[Category:Virtue]]\n", "text_old": "'''Coitus reservatus''' (''[[Sexual intercourse|coitus]]'', \"sexual intercourse, union\" + ''reservatus'', \"reserved, saved\"),<ref>Cassell's ''Compact Latin Dictionary'', Dell Publishing Co. Inc., 1963</ref> also known as '''sexual continence''', is a form of sexual intercourse in which the penetrative partner does not attempt to [[Ejaculation|ejaculate]] within the receptive partner, but instead attempts to remain at the [[Human sexual response cycle#Plateau phase|plateau phase]] of intercourse for as long as possible, avoiding the seminal emission. It is distinct from [[death grip syndrome]] wherein the male has no volition in his emissionless state.<ref>Levin, Roy J. \"Male Sexual Arousal and Orgasms\u2014New Enigmas of Their Activation.\" Current Sexual Health Reports 10.3 (2018): 76-78.</ref>\n\n[[Alice Stockham]] coined the term ''karezza'', derived from the Italian word \"carezza\" meaning \"caress\", to describe coitus reservatus, but the idea was already in practice at the [[Oneida Community]]. [[Alan Watts]] believed, in error, that karezza was a Persian word.<ref>{{cite book |last=Watts |first=Alan W. |title=Nature, Man and Woman |url=https://archive.org/details/naturemanwoman00watt |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/naturemanwoman00watt/page/172 172] |year=1970 |publisher=Random House Inc. Vintage Books Edition |lccn=58-8266 }}</ref> The concept of karezza is loosely akin to [[maithuna]] in [[Tantra|Hindu Tantra]] and [[Sahaja]] in Hindu [[Yoga]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Coomaraswami |first=Ananda K.|title=The Dance of Shiva |page=124 |publisher=The Noonday Press Inc. |year=1957 |location=New York City |lccn=56-12296}}</ref>\n\nControl of ejaculation is a key aspect of [[Taoist sexual practices]] (known as \"cai Yin pu Yang\" and \"cai Yang pu Yin\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/GESUND/ARCHIV/SEN/CH23.HTM|title=Human Sexuality: An Encyclopedia: T|last=Pauly|first=Ira B.|date=2013-05-23|publisher=Humboldt-Universit\u00e4t zu Berlin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523194332/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/GESUND/ARCHIV/SEN/CH23.HTM|archive-date=2013-05-23|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-06-18}}</ref>\n\n== Practice of Karezza and Tantric (sexual) continence ==\n\nStockham writes, \"... Karezza signifies 'to express affection in both words and action,' and while it fittingly denotes the union that is the outcome of deepest human affection, love's consummation, it is used technically throughout this work to designate a controlled sexual union.\" So that in practice, according to Stockham, it is more than just self-control, but mutual control where the penetrative partner helps the receptive partner and vice versa. According to Stockham this is the key to overcoming many difficulties encountered in trying to control sexual expression on an individual basis.{{sfn |Stockham |1896 |p=22}}\nStockham's contribution was to apply this same philosophy of [[Edging (sexual practice)|orgasm control]] to women as much as to men. A form of [[birth control]], the technique also prolongs sexual pleasure to the point of achieving mystical ecstasy, according to [[John William Lloyd|J. William Lloyd]], a practitioner of Karezza, whose own experience of [[cosmic consciousness]] appears in  ''Cosmic Consciousness'', a book written  by the Canadian psychiatrist [[Richard Maurice Bucke|Richard M. Bucke]], a friend of the American poet [[Walt Whitman]].<ref>Bucke, Richard Maurice, M. D. ''Cosmic Consciousness'', p. 284, Citadel Press, 1961, {{ISBN|0-8065-0211-8}}</ref> In this practice,  orgasm is separated from ejaculation, making possible enjoyment of the pleasure of sexual intercourse without experiencing seminal ejaculation, while still experiencing orgasm.\n\nSome would have the principles of karezza applied to masturbation, whereby a person attempts to delay orgasm as long as possible to prolong pleasure in a process known as \"orgasmic brinkmanship\", \"surfing\", or \"edging,\" but this is different from the heterosexual practice of \"karezza\".<ref>Ruth Marie Griffith ''Born Again Bodies'', p. 92, [[University of California Press]], 2004 {{ISBN|978-0-520-24240-1}}</ref> In Latin literature, this is known as ''coitus sine ejaculatione seminis''.<ref>Lloyd, J. William ''The Karezza Method'' Health Research, 1964, Mokelumne Hill, California</ref>\n\nOne purpose of karezza is the maintenance, and indeed, intensification of desire and enjoyment of sexual pleasure within the context of  relationships. According to Stockham, it takes from two weeks to a month for the body to recover from ejaculation ... \"Unless procreation is desired, let the final propagative orgasm be entirely avoided\".{{sfn |Stockham |1896 |p=25}} Stockham advocated that the 'honeymoon period' of a relationship could be maintained in perpetuity by limiting the frequency of ejaculations, or, preferably avoiding them entirely.{{sfn |Stockham |1896 |p=15}}\n\nKalman Andras Oszlar writes, \"Inasmuch as sexual togetherness is not limited into the physical world and does not mean quick wasting of sexual energies, by this we give free way to higher dimensions in the relationship.\" Affected by this, we may get into the state of flow, and in the course of this, the couple charges up with energy, while \u2013 with focused attention ([[Dh\u0101ra\u1e47\u0101]]) \u2013 the couple is submerging in that in which they are having pleasure. This state of mind is connected with the achieved beneficial effects by tantric restraint and transformation. At first, the definition of positive philosophy was defined by [[Mih\u00e1ly Cs\u00edkszentmih\u00e1lyi]], and since then it is referred beyond the professional line. According to the professor, the flow experience is an entirely focused and a motivationally intensified experience where in the course of this people can entirely focus and properly command their feelings for the best performance or learning.\n\n===General===\nThere is a slight difference between karezza and coitus reservatus.  In coitus reservatus, unlike karezza, a woman can enjoy a prolonged orgasm while a man exercises self-control.<ref name=\"Urban 1949\">{{cite web | last=Urban | first=Rudolf von | title=Sex perfection and marital happiness | publisher=Dial Press | year=1949 | oclc=688412035 | url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/api/volumes/oclc/14678823.html | access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n\nLike [[coitus interruptus]], coitus reservatus is not a reliable form of preventing a [[sexually transmitted disease]], as the penis leaks [[pre-ejaculate]] prior to ejaculation, which may contain all of the same infectious viral particles and bacteria as the [[semen]]. Although studies have not found sperm in pre-ejaculate fluid,<ref>{{cite journal\n|title=Researchers find no sperm in pre-ejaculate fluid\n|journal = Contraceptive Technology Update\n|volume = 14 | issue = 10 |pages=154\u2013156 |date=October 1993 | pmid = 12286905 }}\n</ref><ref name=\"pre-e study\">{{cite journal\n|last=Zukerman |first=Z. |author2=Weiss D.B. Orvieto R.\n|title=Short Communication: Does Preejaculatory Penile Secretion Originating from Cowper's Gland Contain Sperm?\n|journal = Journal of Assisted Reproduction and Genetics\n| volume = 20 | issue = 4 |pages=157\u2013159 |date=April 2003 | pmid = 12762415 |doi = 10.1023/A:1022933320700 | pmc=3455634}}\n</ref> the method is also unreliable for [[contraception]] because of the difficulty of controlling ejaculation beyond the point of no return. Additionally, it is possible for pre-ejaculate fluid to collect sperm from a previous ejaculation, leading to pregnancy even when performed correctly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Withdrawal Method |work=Planned Parenthood |date=March 2004 | url =http://www.plannedparenthood.com/health-topics/birth-control/withdrawal-pull-out-method-4218.htm |accessdate=2008-03-28 }}</ref>\n\n===Views on ''coitus reservatus''===\nThe [[Oneida Community]], founded in the 19th century by [[John Humphrey Noyes]], experimented with coitus reservatus which was then called '''male continence''' in a religiously [[Christianity|Christian]] [[communalism|communalist]] environment. The experiment lasted for about a quarter of a century and then Noyes went on to create Oneida silverware and establish the Oneida Silver Co. that grew into [[Oneida Limited]].{{sfn |Ellis |1910 |p=553}}  Noyes identified three functions of the sexual organs: the urinary, the propagative, and the amative. Noyes believed in the separation of the amative from the propagative, and he put amative sexual intercourse on the same footing with other ordinary forms of social interchange. Sexual intercourse as Noyes defines it is the insertion of the penis into the vagina; ejaculation is not a requirement for sexual intercourse.<ref name=\"Noyes 1872\">{{cite book |title=Male continence |website=Syracuse University Library - Department of Special Collections - Oneida Community Collection |authorlink=John Humphrey Noyes |first=John Humphrey |last=Noyes |archiveurl=https://iiif.lib.harvard.edu/manifests/view/drs:2577486$1i |archivedate=2017-11-03 |url-status=live |year=1877 |orig-year=1872 |location=Oneida, NY |publisher=Office of the American Socialist |oclc=786280936 |url=https://library.syr.edu/digital/collections/m/MaleContinence-51k/}}</ref>\n\nEnglish novelist [[Aldous Huxley]], in his last novel ''Island'' wrote that Maithuna, the Yoga of Love is \"the same as what [[Roman Catholicism]] means by ''coitus reservatus''.\"<ref>Huxley, Aldous ''Island, Harper & Row, 1962''</ref> Getting to the point by discussing ''coitus reservatus'', Alan W. Watts in ''Nature, Man and Woman'' notes: \"...I would like to see someone make a case for the idea that the [[Apostles]] really did hand down an inner tradition to the Church, and that through all these centuries the Church has managed to guard it from the public eye. If so, it has remained far more secret and [[esotericism|\"esoteric\"]] than in any of the other great spiritual traditions of the world, so much so that its existence is highly doubtful...\"<ref>\"Watts, Alan W. ''Nature, Man and Woman, Ch 7, Pantheon Books Inc. 1958''</ref> The Welsh writer [[Norman Lewis (author)|Norman Lewis]], in his celebrated account of life in [[Naples]] in 1944, claimed that [[Saint Roch|San Rocco]] was the [[patron saint]] of coitus reservatus:  \"I recommended him to drink -- as the locals did -- [[Marsala wine|marsala]] with the yolk of eggs stirred into it, and to wear a medal of San Rocco, patron of coitus reservatus, which could be had in any religious-supplies shop\".<ref name=\"Lewis 2005 p. \">{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Norman |title=Naples '44 : a World War II diary of occupied Italy |publisher=Carroll & Graf |location=New York |year=2005 |isbn=9781480433250 |oclc=854852494 }}</ref> The psychologist [[Havelock Ellis]] writes: \"''Coitus Reservatus'', \u2013 in which intercourse is maintained even for very long periods, during which a woman may orgasm several times while the penetrative partner succeeds in holding back orgasm \u2013 so far from being injurious to a woman, is probably the form of coitus which gives her the maximum gratification and relief\".{{sfn|Ellis|1910|p=552}}\n\n=== Catholic Church and Coitus Reservatus ===\nThe Catholic Church does allow ''coitus reservatus'':\n\n* St. [[Alphonsus Liguori]] allows it in marriage, if mutual (when both spouses restrain themselves from orgasm).<ref>{{cite book|title=Innocent Ecstasy: How Christianity Gave America an Ethic of Sexual Pleasure|last=Gardell|first=Peter|page=14\u201316|year=1985|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York and Oxford|isbn=9780195365153|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=VV_GNSx-vy4C&dq=%22amplexus+reservatus%22&pg=PA14&lpg=PA16}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book|title=Innocent Ecstasy, Updated Edition: How Christianity Gave America an Ethic of Sexual Pleasure|last=Gardell|first=Peter|page=22|year=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York and Oxford|isbn=9780190609429|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=EP7mDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT22&lpg=PT22&dq=liguori+%22amplexus+reservatus%22}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book|title=Theologiae Moralis|last=Liguori|first=Alphonsus|year=1748}}</ref> [[Moral Theology (Liguori)]]\n* [[Holy_See]] allows this practice in volume number 44<ref>https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-44-1952-ocr.pdf page 548</ref> of [[Acta Apostolicae Sedis]]. It refers to it under the Latin term \"amplexus reservatus\" (reserved embrace): \"contra \u00abamplexum reservatum\u00bb nihil esset obiicendum\" - \"nothing is objectionable\", so it's allowed.\n* [[John F. Harvey]] OSFS confirmed and explained ''coitus reservatus''. The spouses should avoid undue frustration. They must not intend orgasm for either of them. <ref>{{cite book|title=International Review of Natural Family Planning|page=211\u2013212|year=1981|url=http://www.usccb.org/issues-and-action/marriage-and-family/natural-family-planning/what-is-nfp/science/upload/intl-review-nfp-1981-harvey-expressing-marital-love-during-fertile-phase.pdf}}</ref> If unintentionally one of them reaches the climax, then they must try to stimulate the other spouse to reach the climax, too. <ref>{{cite book|title=Difficult Moral Questions, Question 29: What sexual activity is permissible...|year=1997|last=Professor Grisez|first=Germain|publisher=Franciscan Press, Quincy University|location=Quincy, Illinois, USA|url=http://www.twotlj.org/G-3-29.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Living a Christian Life, Chapter 9: Marriage, Sexual Acts, and Family Life, Question E: What Sexual Acts Are Appropriate for Christians?|year=1992|last=Professor Grisez|first=Germain|publisher=Franciscan Press, Quincy University|location=Quincy, Illinois, USA|url=http://www.twotlj.org/G-2-9-E.html}}</ref><ref>See http://www.twotlj.org/grisez_collaborators.html for the team credentials, http://www.twotlj.org for \"Nihil obstat\" and \"Imprimatur\".</ref>\n\nThat differs from how one author uses the same term \"amplexus reservatus\" for non-penetrative, rubbing-only sex.<ref name=\"Bullough 2001 p.\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of birth control|last=Bullough|first=Vern|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2001|isbn=9781576075333|location=Santa Barbara, Calif|page=|oclc=50174689}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=XuX-MGTZnJoC&pg=PA75&lpg=PA76&dq=reservatus |title = Encyclopedia of Birth Control|isbn = 9781576071816|last1 = Bullough|first1 = Vern L.|year = 2001}}</ref> The same source claims that ''coitus reservatus'' is subject to the same arguments as [[Coitus interruptus]], but with no citation at all.\n\nAnother author wrote that the Catholic Church condemned this practice.<ref>{{cite book|title=Enchiridion Symbolorum|last=Denzinger|first=Heinrich|publisher=Ignatius Press|year=2012|isbn=9780898707465|location=San Francisco, Calif|page=810}}</ref> However, that condemnation is contrary to official Catholic teaching referenced above.\n<br />\n\n== Rosicrucians ==\nThe [[AMORC]] [[Rosicrucians]] declare openly that they do not engage in sexual practices of an occult nature. This has been so since their First Imperator [[H. Spencer Lewis]], Ph. D. made it public knowledge.<ref>Lewis, H. Spencer ''Rosicrucian Manual'', p. 5, Supreme Grand Lodge of AMORC, 1978</ref> Their rival organization [[Fraternitas Rosae Crucis]] led by Dr. [[R. Swinburne Clymer]] engages in sexual practices for the sake of race regeneration. Dr. Clymer is completely opposed to the practice of Karezza or ''coitus reservatus'' and advocates instead a form of sex intercourse in which the couple experiences the orgasm at the same time.<ref>Clymer, R. Swinburne MD, ''The Mystery of Sex and Race Regeneration'', p. 223, The Philosophical Publishing Co., 1950</ref> The Secretary of the [[FUDOSI]] instead heartily approves the practice of Karezza to establish harmony in the family as well as in the world by preventing the waste and misuse of sex energy.<ref>Marc Lanval, editor, ''Lumi\u00e8re et Libert\u00e9'', Organe Officiel de la Ligue Belge de Propagande H\u00e9liophile, Octobre-Novembre 1933</ref>\n\nDr. [[Arnold Krumm-Heller]] established the [[Fraternitas Rosicruciana Antiqua]] (FRA), a Rosicrucian school in Germany with branches in South America, having the following formula of sexual conduct: \"Immissio Membri Virile In Vaginae Sine Ejaculatio Seminis\" (Introduce the penis in the vagina without ejaculating the semen). [[Samael Aun Weor]] experimented with that formula and developed the doctrine of ''[[The Perfect Matrimony]]''.\n\n== \"Dianism\" in Sex Magick == \n{{main|Dianism}}\nInspired by [[Ida Craddock]]'s work Heavenly Bridegrooms, American occultist [[C.F. Russell]] developed his own curriculum of [[sex magick]].<ref name=\"google.com2\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yFs3qoTFVz8C&pg=PA12|title=The Complete Magick Curriculum of the Secret Order G.B.G.|publisher=|isbn=9780738726748|last1=Culling|first1=Louis T.|last2=Weschcke|first2=Carl Llewellyn|date=8 September 2010}}</ref>  In the 1960s, disciple Louis T. Culling published these in two works entitled ''The Complete Magickal Curriculum of the Secret Order G.'.B.'.G.'.'' and ''Sex Magick''.<ref>{{Cite book|isbn=978-0-7387-1912-2|title=The Complete Magick Curriculum of the Secret Order G.B.G.: Being the Entire Study, Curriculum, Magick Rituals, and Initiatory Practices of the G.B.G (The Great Brotherhood of God)|author= Louis T. Culling, Carl Llewellyn Weschcke|date=8 September 2010|publisher=}}</ref>  The first two degrees are \"Alphaism and Dianism\".<ref name=\"google.com1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IoybRLX4jqIC&pg=PA244|title=Sexual Outlaw, Erotic Mystic|publisher=|isbn=9781609252960|last1=Chappell|first1=Vere|date=December 2010}}, Chappell, V. (2010). Sexual outlaw, erotic mystic: The essential Ida Craddock. San Francisco, CA: Red Wheel/Weiser.</ref><ref name=\"google.com2\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yFs3qoTFVz8C&pg=PA12|title=The Complete Magick Curriculum of the Secret Order G.B.G.|publisher=|isbn=9780738726748|last1=Culling|first1=Louis T.|last2=Weschcke|first2=Carl Llewellyn|date=8 September 2010}}</ref> Culling writes that Dianism is \"sexual congress without bringing it to climax\" and that each participant is to regard their partner not as a \"known earthly personality\" but as a \"visible manifestation of one's [[Holy Guardian Angel]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yFs3qoTFVz8C&pg=PA127|title=The Complete Magick Curriculum of the Secret Order G.B.G.: Being the Entire Study, Curriculum, Magick Rituals, and Initiatory Practices of the G.B.G (The Great Brotherhood of God)|last=Culling|first=Louis T.|last2=Weschcke|first2=Carl Llewellyn|publisher=Llewellyn Worldwide|year=2010|isbn=9780738726748|location=|pages=|language=en|oclc=793421982}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n[[Alice Bunker Stockham|Alice Stockham]] was taken to court and forced to give up teaching the practice of Karezza in the [[United States]]. Like many other sex reformers, Dr. Stockham was arrested by [[Anthony Comstock]].<ref>John P. Deveney ''Paschal B. Randolph'', p. 393, SUNY Press, 1997 {{ISBN|978-0-7914-3119-1}}</ref> He jailed for long terms a variety of spiritual marriage reformers including [[Paschal Beverly Randolph]] who had been a personal friend of [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref>Paschal B. Randolph ''Ravalette: The Rosicrucian's Story'', p. 64, Kessinger Publishing, 2005 {{ISBN|978-0-7661-9160-0}}</ref> [[Ida Craddock]] committed [[suicide in the United States|suicide]] after being repeatedly jailed for peddling [[pornography]].<ref>Vern L. Bullough ''Encyclopedia of Birth Control'', pp. 76-9, ABC-CLIO, 2001 {{ISBN|978-1-57607-181-6}}</ref> The [[Oneida Community]] was attacked in the press and Noyes was forced to flee to [[Canada]] due to a warrant being issued for his arrest on a [[statutory rape]] charge on June 22, 1879. From there, he advised others to follow [[St. Paul]]'s plan of either [[marriage]] or [[celibacy]], and to obey the [[Ten Commandments|commandments]] against [[adultery]] and [[fornication]].<ref>Patricia Gutek ''Visiting Utopian Communities'', p. 137, [[University of South Carolina Press]], 1998 {{ISBN|978-1-57003-210-3}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Human sexuality}}\n* [[Coitus interruptus]]\n* [[Coitus saxonicus]]\n* [[Eroto-comatose lucidity]]\n* [[Orgone]]\n* [[Sex magic]]\n* [[Venus Butterfly]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Ellis |first=Havelock |authorlink=Havelock Ellis |title=Studies in the psychology of sex. |website=Wellcome Library |url=http://wellcomelibrary.org/item/b18033659 |access-date=2017-11-03 |oclc=927688075 |year=1910 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=F.A. Davis |asin=B008499I5C |volume=Volume 6 Sex in Relation to Society |ref=harv}} <br/>Republished: {{cite book |last=Ellis |first=Havelock |title=Studies in the psychology of sex |publisher=Anboco |location=Dinslaken |year=2016 |isbn=9783736412088 |oclc=958563038 |volume=Volume 6 Sex in Relation to Society}}\n*{{cite web | last=Lloyd | first=J. William | title=The Karezza Method Index | website=Internet Sacred Text Archive Home | url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/sex/krz/index.htm | access-date=2017-11-03}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Lloyd\n|first=John William\n|authorlink=John William Lloyd\n|title=The Karezza Method or Magnetation: The Art of Connubial Love\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Rp3QveSUjEC\n|accessdate=7 March 2011\n|year=1931\n|publisher=Forgotten Books\n|isbn=978-1-60620-046-9}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Robinson\n|first=Marnia\n|authorlink=Marnia Robinson\n|title=Cupid's Poisoned Arrow: From Habit to Harmony in Sexual Relationships\n|url=\n|accessdate=\n|year=2009\n|publisher=North Atlantic Books\n|isbn=9781556438097}}\n*{{cite book| title=Karezza, Ethics of Marriage Index | website=Internet Sacred Text Archive Home | url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/sex/eom/index.htm | access-date=2017-11-03 |authorlink=Alice Bunker Stockham |first=Alice Bunker |last=Stockham |location=New York |publisher=R.F. Fenno and Co. |year=1896 |oclc=868004523 |ref=harv}} Also available as {{cite book |last=Stockham |first=Alice |title=Karezza Ethics of Marriage |publisher=Books on Demand |location=Norderstedt |year=2017 |isbn=9783744815086 |oclc=987572577}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Urban\n|first=Rudolf Von\n|authorlink=Rudolf von Urban